<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Leaders Meet in Beijing  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting American religious
leaders met with their Chinese counterparts today to discuss
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Rabbi Arthur Schneier, president of the Appeal of Conscience
Foundation, Archbishop Theodore McCarrick of the Newark Roman
Catholic Archdiocese and Reverend Don Argue, president of the
National Association of Evangelicals, and their party are visiting
China as guests of the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Bishop Fu Tieshan briefed the American delegation on the history
and the current status of Catholicism in China.
</P>
<P>
China is currently home to 115 Catholic diocese, 5000-odd
churches, more than 1000 priests and over four million Catholics,
according to Bishop Fu, who also serves as president of the Chinese
Catholic Patriotic Association (CCPA).
</P>
<P>
Approximately 60,000 people are baptized into the Catholic
faith annually, according to the bishop.
</P>
<P>
Fu recounted the 700-odd year history of Catholicism in China,
and noted that the spread of the religion has been suited to
Chinese culture and local customs.
</P>
<P>
Bishop Fu voiced anxiety about the problem of aging amongst the
Catholic clergy. He held that the CCPA should devote itself to the
management of seminaries so as to train more young clergymen in
philosophy and theology.
</P>
<P>
The CCPA operates 31 seminaries which have trained more than
900 priests over the past two-odd decades.
</P>
<P>
CCPA Vice-President Liu Bonian told the American visitors that
a group of young bishops have completed their education and are
preparing to assume positions. He said that Catholicism will
witness a period of still more rapid development over the next ten
years.
</P>
<P>
Archbishop McCarrick volunteered to help train teachers for
China's seminaries.
</P>
<P>
Schneier expressed encouragement about charities organized by
the CCPA and asked about efforts to educate children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
