<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President: Military Threat Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
Wednesday observed that there appears no relaxation of a military
threat against Iraq as the U.S. is augmenting its military
presence in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"What I fear is Iraq coming under a strike for failure to
implement the (U.N.) resolutions. And no one would then be able to
prevent the U.S. from mounting such a blow," Mubarak told
reporters on the possibility of a military option.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement to reporters after hour-long talks with
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed al-Sahhaf who arrived here
Wednesday morning to drum up Arab support for avoiding threatened
U.S. military strikes.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been subjected to U.S. threat of military action over
its denial of full access to the U.N. arms inspectors to its
presidential sites suspected of hiding lethal weapons, and its
demand for a re-formation of the inspection teams.
</P>
<P>
"I see a large military buildup already in place," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the president also denied mass media reports that
there is a collective Arab initiative to solve the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Such initiative should emanate from all the Arab states and
this did not happen," Mubarak told reporters, adding he received
no word on such an initiative and that there is no tendency at
present to hold even a limited Arab summit.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi foreign minister told reporters here Wednesday that
Iraq has agreed to open eight presidential sites to international
arms inspectors appointed by the U.N. Secretary General.
</P>
<P>
He explained that "When we say eight we are actually talking
about all the sites," in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Amidst diplomatic efforts by Russia, France and the Arab
League, a proposal for a solution has been taking shape, which
allows U.N. inspectors access to the eight presidential palaces
and 60 other sites.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said he told Sahhaf the situation is grave and the
Security Council resolutions should be executed so as to avoid any
aggravations.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he had felt a flexible Iraqi stand following his
meeting with Sahhaf, Mubarak said "I told him all I wanted and the
decision is theirs." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
