<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Searches for Way out of SRM Impasse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The European commissioners
held a round-table debate on Wednesday in an attempt to iron out
the remaining difficulties surrounding the implementation of the
European Union's ban on specified risk materials (SRM).
</P>
<P>
They had to deal with this thorny issue as a full team now that
France announced on Monday that it had reversed its earlier
decision not to comply with the union's directive on the treatment
of SRMs.
</P>
<P>
The commissioners discussed the persistent resistance to the
treatment of SRMs, that are certain categories of livestock offal
that present a high risk of infection from Bovine Spongiform
Encephalopathy or madcow disease.
</P>
<P>
The resistance comes from Germany, Austria, Denmark, Finland,
Spain and Greece that have formally applied to the European
Commission for TSE-free status.
</P>
<P>
TSE is transmissible spongiform encephalopathies that include
BSE and scrapie in sheep.
</P>
<P>
All six countries are actually demanding a de facto exemption
from the SRM ban and they have threatened to block all BSE-related
legislation until the commission provides assurances that their
applications for TSE-free status are treated seriously.
</P>
<P>
A proposal can become an EU legislation only after all the 15
European Union member states agree upon it.
</P>
<P>
The six countries emitted their threat in relation to
Australia's and New Zealand's application for TSE-free status,
which was indefinitely shelved by the European Union Standing
Veterinary Committee.
</P>
<P>
The commissioners also discussed about the long-running dispute
with the United States over its EU-bound exports of tallow-based
pharmaceuticals that are worth 4.5 billion U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The tallow-based pharmaceuticals, under a strict interpretation
of the SRM ban, will have to be suspended altogether.
</P>
<P>
The American side has protested in the strongest possible terms
and underlined its opposition last December by suspending all
imports of live ruminants and ruminant meat from the European
Union on the grounds that it could no longer ignore their inherent
risk of BSE infection.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
union, had planned to implement the SRM ban on January 1 this year
but had to postpone it till March 31 under opposition from both EU
member states and third country trading partners.
</P>
<P>
The one-day debate seemed not enough to help remove the
uncertainty still hanging on the SRM ban. 
</P>
</TEXT>
