<HEADLINE> Russian Special Plane Enroute to Bagdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A Russian IL-86 special
aircraft carrying a Duma delegation and humanitarian cargo left
for Iraq from Ereven, the capital of Armenia on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Aboard the plane were 12 tons of relief supplies and 32 people,
including nine Duma (parliament) deputies, 15 reporters and eight
people accompanying the cargo.
</P>
<P>
The plane, which had been waiting on the ground in Armenia
since Sunday, won permission for the flight from the United
Nations' Iraqi sanctions committee Wednesday morning, said the
Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
The plane's departure was delayed because there is a national
holiday in Iran, Interfax cited the State Duma Chairman Gennady
Seleznyov as saying.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Duma delegation to Iraq, Vladimir Zhirinovsky,
Wednesday morning tried to get a maximum possible number of
deputies, journalists and other people onto the plane. But the
U.N. committee restricted the number of people aboard.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Russian Regions parliamentary group issued a
statement expressing grave concern over the Iraqi situation.
</P>
<P>
However, it said the populist show staged by the Liberal
Democratic Party, leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky has nothing to do
with standing up for Russia's national interests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
