<HEADLINE> Feature: Spring Lantern Festival in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 11 (Xinhua) -- "The full moon hanging in
the sky tonight not only symbolizes Hong Kong's return to the
motherland, but also predicts a bright future of the special
region," said Chan Loo Shan here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chan, 38, together with his four-member family, was among the
thousands of people who flocked to the Ko Shan Park and Theater
Wednesday evening, where they could have a glimpse of the gigantic
lantern and enjoy a variety of entertainment programs in
celebration of the traditional Chinese Lantern Carnival.
</P>
<P>
Besides marveling at the eight-meter lantern called "Blossoming
Flowers in Celebration of Spring," the crowd took part in free
programs including Chinese comic talk shows and concerts by
renowned Guangdong Music Company from Guangzhou and an exciting
traditional stage art show by a famous local troupe.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the switching-on ceremony, Chairman of the
Provisional Urban Council's Entertainment Select Committee
Christina Ting Yuk-chee said that the local government is glad to
celebrate the Spring Lantern Festival together with the public on
this festive occasion.
</P>
<P>
While the Ko Shan Park was full of a festive mood, a variety of
 Chinese traditional dances performed by the Hong Kong Dance
Company and Hong Kong Folk Dance Troupe as well as romantic
Chinese opera excerpts by Ching Fai Cantonese Opera College were
offered inside Ko Shan Theater.
</P>
<P>
In addition, visitors spent a joyful evening participating in
different activities including lantern corridor exhibition,
lantern riddle games, Chinese calligraphy, grasshopper-making and
stone painting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other Spring Lantern Festival celebrations were held
at Tuen Mun Park and Tuen Mun Cultural Square, on Cheung Chau and
in Fanling, featuring giant lantern display, versatile stage
performances and games stalls.
</P>
<P>
A 40-feet dragon lantern, a 15-feet palace lantern and some 40
lanterns were displayed at Tuen Mun Park and the Tuen Mun Cultural
Square.
</P>
<P>
There were also performances of Beijing opera, magic and
children's martial art. To enhance the festive mood on the
"Chinese Valentine's Day," pop singers including Dry, Edmond Leung
and Anodize sang love songs at the carnival.
</P>
<P>
However, most local citizens enjoyed the full moon at home or
celebrated the festival by partying in restaurants or going
shopping and watching films.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
