<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-11 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urged to Respond to Tension-Defusing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers of the
six-member Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Wednesday urged Iraq to
respond positively to the international efforts aimed at defusing
the current crisis over weapons inspection.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued following their extraordinary meeting
here, the GCC foreign ministers said "the current crisis is a
direct result of Baghdad's reluctance to cooperate with United
Nations inspectors and its determination to defy the will of the
international community with respect to the elimination of its
arsenal of weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic organization
established in 1981, groups Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab
Emirates, Oman, Bahrain and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The ministers said the Iraqi regime was required to implement
the will of the international community represented by the U.N.
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
They deemed as unacceptable the Iraqi unilateral actions which
led to the current Iraqi-U.N. standoff.
</P>
<P>
They also reiterated their support for diplomatic efforts to
defuse the tension.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Sabah said at the opening ceremony that "keen on the safety and
security of the region and aware of the dangers of Iraq's
challenges and the possible consequences that might result from
other options, we have all expressed support" for the international
efforts to find a diplomatic solution.
</P>
<P>
On the U.N. economic sanctions, the ministers held Iraqi
leadership responsible, saying in the statement that "the only
solution to spare the people of Iraq additional hardship and
dangers is the Iraqi regime's implementation of the
U.N. resolutions which it had previously accepted."
</P>
<P>
They also stressed their keenness on the territorial integrity
and sovereignty of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The emergency meeting was mooted by Kuwait in view of growing
tension Iraq and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was triggered by Iraq's denial of free access to
U.N. arms inspectors its presidential sites suspected of hiding
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The United States has threatened to resort to force against
Iraq if the current diplomatic efforts fail to end the
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The GCC leaders called on Iraq to cooperate fully with the
U.N. Special Commission in charge of eliminating Iraqi weapons of
mass destruction and comply with all the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
They also expressed deep concern over the growing tension
between Iraq and the U.N. as a result of Iraq's continued attempts
to conceal biological and chemical weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
