<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Opposition Challenges Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 11 (Xinhua) --The Zimbabwean opposition
National Democratic Union (NDU) today lodged an application in
the Supreme Court, challenging the government's recent
designation of commercial farms for compulsory acquisition under
the controversial land resettlement scheme.
</P>
<P>
In the application, NDU President Mark Muchabaiwa cites
Minister of Lands ane Agriculture Kumbirai Kangai as the
respondent in his capacity as the Administrator of the Land
Acquisition Act.
</P>
<P>
The NDU application follows the designation late last year of
more than 1,400 commercial farms for compulsory acquisition,
mostly owned by the country's 4,500 white farmers.
</P>
<P>
The land acquisition act and the constitution require full
payment of compensation for property acquired by the state, but
the government said it would only compensate for improvements
without considering the value of the land.
</P>
<P>
NDU is seeking an interdict suspending of the whole
designation exercise until the compensation ratio is agreed upon
and rationalised.
</P>
<P>
''It is also important to note the manner in which the
exercise is being carried out is in clear violation of the
citizen's constitutional rights to their property and their
rights to seek recourse to the law in case of a dispute with the
government,'' the party said in the application.
</P>
<P>
The government is determined to resolve the situation of
imbalance of the land. At present, less than one present of the
country's population, the white farmers, owned about 70 percent
of the land.
</P>
<P>
Last week, President Robert Mugabe said his government was
trying to resolve the land issue in a peaceful and orderly
manner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
