<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal Launches Poverty Alleviation Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali government has
launched a poverty alleviation project in eight districts of
western Terai, the official RSS news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The project aims to enhance the income generation of the small
farmers, the landless and underprivileged women, take ahead the
targeted persons toward sustainable development by organizing them
in small groups and strengthen the financial efficiency of the
financial bodies engaged in providing loan services for
sustainable development, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The project is being implemented by adopting the concept of
group development which is considered successful in the developing
countries, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 107,805 people will benefit from the project during
a seven-year period, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost some 9.73 million U.S. dollars. The
International Fund for Agriculture Development agreed last
December to provide a loan of 8.87 million dollars, while the rest
will be covered by the Nepali government, the beneficiaries and
Nepal's Agriculture Development Bank, the RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The Terai plain in southern Nepal is a major grain producer of
the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
