<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Secondhand Smoke Causes Ear Infections of Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A major Canadian study has
found that children can get painful middle-ear infections from
second-hand smoke at home.
</P>
<P>
Children who lived with two or more smokers for their first
three years were shown to have an 85-percent higher risk of
developing the infection than those who were not exposed to smoke,
according to the study done by University of Calgary researchers.
</P>
<P>
Preschoolers whose mothers smoked more than 10 cigarettes a day
showed a 68-percent higher chance of suffering from the disease,
whose symptoms include pain, loss of sleep and temperature
spiking.
</P>
<P>
In Canada, about 13 percent of middle-ear infection among urban
children stems from passive smoking.
</P>
<P>
These findings have been published in the American Medical
Association Archive of Pediatrics &AMP; Adolescent Medicine, the Globe
and Mail newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Middle-ear disease can lead to short-term or long-term hearing
loss, slow language development and other serious complications,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 625 Grade 1 pupils from 36 schools were involved in
the study, the most thorough and representative of a series of
North American studies that sought to establish whether there is a
link between secondhand smoke and ear-infections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
