<HEADLINE> Beijing Reaffirms Ban on Fireworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Beijing, the Chinese capital,
reaffirmed the ban on fireworks and instructed related departments
to strictly enforce related regulations during today's
celebrations of the traditional Lantern Festival.
</P>
<P>
A city official denied rumors that the municipal government
will relax controls on fireworks. Related regulations, approved by
the Standing Committee of the Municipal People's Congress, have
been in effect since 1993.
</P>
<P>
An increasing number of Beijingers violated regulations by
discharging fireworks during this year's Spring Festival, the
Chinese lunar New Year's day.
</P>
<P>
The cancellation of fireworks ban in some cities,
including Luoyang and Hangzhou, sparked rumors about relaxed
regulations in the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
The official attributed the increasing number of cases of the
illegal use of fireworks to lax monitoring by the related
departments and the approved use of fireworks in suburban areas
since last year.
</P>
<P>
Local public security departments have fined 350 Beijingers for
related violations, with an additional 17 people detained for the
illegal use of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
Over 300,000 yuan (37,500 US dollars) worth of illegal
fireworks have been confiscated, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Environmental Protection Agency reported the
average noise level during this year's Spring Festival exceeded
the state-set standard of 55 decibels for the first time since
initiation of the ban five years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Fire Department reported 236 fires during the
Spring Festival holidays from January 28 to February 1. Of them,
59 cases were attributed directly to fireworks.
</P>
<P>
"The figure was significantly larger than in the previous
year," said an official in the fire department.
</P>
<P>
A survey of Beijing's major hospitals revealed that more people
were injured by fireworks during this year's Spring Festival than
in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Local newspapers report that 24 Beijingers were seriously
injured by fireworks last week, with at least nine losing their
eyesight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Insurance Giant Allianz Posts Big Profit Gains </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Germany's largest insurance group
Allianz Wednesday announced a pre-tax profit of 4.95 billion marks
(2.72 billion U.S. dollars) for 1997, up nearly 19 percent from a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
Allianz today also reported a group turnover of 85.3 billion
marks (46.9 billion dollars) in 1997, up 14 percent from the 1996
level.
</P>
<P>
For 1998, Allianz expects its turnover to increase by nearly
four percent to 88 billion marks (48.4 billion dollars), with
profit expected to grow faster than turnover again.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Allianz's planned takeover of the third largest
French insurer Assurances Generales de France SA (AGF) would also
add some 26 billion marks (14.3 billion dollars) to the German
group's total turnover, making it the largest insurer in the
world, the company said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
