<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Seminar on Rights of Disabled Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A three-day international
seminar on the U.N. rules on disability began here Wednesday to
discuss ways to guarantee the disabled the same rights as the
able ones.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 participants from member states of the African
Rehabilitation Institute, the International Labor Organization
and the International Disability Foundation are attending the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The seminar came in the wake of a growing realization that the
situation of the disabled had not changed much despite the
declaration of the world program of action 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Third world countries in particular had not protected the
right of the disabled persons due to various reasons related to
the absence of disability policies.
</P>
<P>
In her opening address, Zimbabwean Public Service, Labor and
Social Welfare Minister Florence Chitauro said the plight of most
disabled people in Africa had not changed much.
</P>
<P>
She said that African countries should do more to learn how to
effectively support the implementation of U.N. policies to
improve the lot of people who had been marginalized for a long
time.
</P>
<P>
President of Pan African Disabled Federation Khalfa Khalfa
called on the African governments to keep have the disabled
people in mind when formulating development policies.
</P>
<P>
He criticized governments for leaving needs of the disabled to
charities.
</P>
<P>
"This is a wrong concept," he said, adding "UN instruments on
disability clearly state that it is the responsibility of the
governments to see that people with disabilities have access to
and enjoy all facilities being enjoyed by the able bodied."
</P>
<P>
Some of the major issues to be discussed include creating
health care opportunities for women with disabilities and the
roles played by international and regional organizations in the
promotion of international disability standard rules. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
