<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe to Phase out Tariffs on Imports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A senior Zimbabwean official
Wednesday called on companies to be prepared for external
competition as the government plans to phase out tariffs on
imports.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira said most
companies had in the past been shielded from imports.
</P>
<P>
"I would like, however, to inform you that my ministry will
soon be undertaking an exercise with a view to phasing down
tariffs. This means that the protection that existed before will
now be progressively scaled down," he said.
</P>
<P>
The present tariff regime, announced last February, protected
local manufacturers by levying duties of between 40 and 85
percent on finished imported products.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said the government had passed the bill
establishing the competition commission, which seeks to cushion
the local industry threatened by unequal external competition.
</P>
<P>
The commission also aims to curb abuse of monopoly power,
prevent restrictive business practices, sanction mergers and
remove barriers to entry into any economic activity.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to take this opportunity to draw the attention
of those who are operating in a monopolistic situation to be
aware that henceforth their action will continuously be monitored
by the watchdog to ensure that all practices are promotive of the
general public of our citizens," he said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks officially opening a Dunlop depot and
distribution center in Harare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
