<HEADLINE> DHKKI in Greece Opposes Military Strike Against Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Greece's Democratic Social
Movement (DHKKI) Wednesday expressed its opposition to the use of
military force against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after his meeting with Iraqi Consul Hazan
Altayar, DHKKI leader Dimitris Tsovolas said that the current
Iraqi crisis with U.N. arms inspectors should not be settled by
resorting to force, but by peaceful means and through diplomatic
channels.
</P>
<P>
He added that it was unacceptable for the Iraqi people to pay,
with a years-long embargo, the designs of the major powers and
their economic interests in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said
Wednesday that the activity at the air bases on the Greek island
of Crete was usual and it was in no way related to developments in
the ongoing Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft of foreign countries whose final destination was
Cyprus had passed through the airports at Souda and Heraklion, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government has insisted that the Iraqi crisis should
be resolved peacefully while U.N. Security Council's resolutions
be implemented by Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Greece says that Washington has so far not yet requested
military assistance or facilities from Athens and it will not
participate in the possible military action against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
