<HEADLINE> Russian Plane Arrives in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A Russian plane carrying an
eight-member delegation headed by Russian Liberal Democratic Party
leader Vladimir Zhirinovsky arrived Wednesday at the Saddam
international airport.
</P>
<P>
The plane, with the Russian State Duma (lower house of
parliament) delegation and a number of Russian reporters on board,
carried eight tonnes of medicine and medical appliances.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi National Assembly (parliament) last week invited the
Russian State Duma to pay visit to its presidential sites, and the
latter accepted Iraq's invitation.
</P>
<P>
The Russian plane, Ilyushin-86, arrived in the Armenian
capital Yerevan Sunday night and was stranded there for two
days before getting a U.N. clearance to fly into Iraq
</P>
<P>
The U.N. clearance for the plane to continue its flight did
not come until Tuesday evening when Zhirinovsky agreed to reduce
the number of people on the plane from some 200 to 31.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant U.N. resolutions, foreign planes to Iraq are
banned after the 1991 Gulf War unless they get clearance from the
U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhirinovsky last visited Baghdad in December with a plane
carrying humanitarian goods to Iraq with the sanctions committee's
exceptional grant.  
</P>
</TEXT>
