<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Opens Info Center on Central, Eastern Europe Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The European Union on
Wednesday opened an information center in Brussels to help
publicize its assistance programs to central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
The information center is aimed at responding more effectively
to information requests about the Phare and Tacis programs from
both the business sector and interest groups.
</P>
<P>
Hans van den Broek, European commissioner in charge of external
relations, attended the opening ceremony of the information
center.
</P>
<P>
The Phare assistance program was initially designed to support
the central European countries in their transition toward market
economy and is now the principal financial instrument for
enlargement.
</P>
<P>
The Tacis assistance program aims to develop harmonious and
prosperous economic and political links with the newly independent
states (NIS) in central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia is also included in this aid program.
</P>
<P>
Together, these two assistance programs have committed almost
10 billion ECU for central and eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
The European Union had set up a smaller information office in
1991 and opened this new information center to deal with the ever
growing demand for information.
</P>
<P>
Last year alone, the old office received an estimated 5,000
visitors and dealt with more than 50,000 letters, faxes, telephone
calls and E-mail messages and gave some 120 presentations.
</P>
<P>
The new center offers personalized assistance and Internet
access as well as documentation.
</P>
<P>
The European Union is central Europe's main trading partner and
by far the main provider of bilateral assistance with a budget of
6.693 billion ECU between 1995 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
The EU is also a major trading partner and main provider of
bilateral assistance to the NIS with a commitment of 3.3 billion
ECU between 1991 and 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain to Introduce Random Drug Tests for Drivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Britain said on Wednesday it
would introduce random roadside drug tests after evidence showed
that drug-influences driving poses a major safety threat.
</P>
<P>
Figures published by the Transport Department showed that 18
percent of drivers killed in accidents had traces of illicit or
medicinal drugs in their bodies, which was far greater than
previously suspected.
</P>
<P>
"What this would do is allow (the police)...to do a quick 'yes
or no' for the presence of drugs at the roadside which then means
they can make a much more informed arrest," said Roads Safety
Minister Baroness Helene Hayman.
</P>
<P>
Under present rules officers who think a motorist is under the
influence of drugs have to arrest the suspect, take them to a
police station and ask for a blood or a urine sample. But now a
few strokes across the forehead with a new testing kit will be
enough to detect illegal substances.
</P>
<P>
Pilot tests will start next month and will be voluntary because
police do not yet have the power to force drivers to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
Officials said the number of people taking drugs and driving
has soared in recent years. One study found that 85 percent of
young drivers in Scotland considered it usual to drive under the
influence of drugs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
