<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-11 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Paints Better Picture of Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Israel Wednesday tried to
paint a better picture of the Palestinian economy in 1997, while
pledging to make more efforts to ease Palestinian lives.
</P>
<P>
Briefing reporters on the economy of the Palestinian self-rule
areas, Yaacov Orr, coordinator of the Government Activities of
Israel in the Occupied Territories, said that in 1997 more
Palestinians were permitted to work in Israel and more Palestinian
merchants and trucks were allowed to travel between the Gaza Strip
and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The days of closure of the Palestinian self-rule areas by
Israel were reduced to 63 days in 1997 from 92 days in 1996, the
number of Palestinians working in Israel increased to 47,000 from
39,000 and Palestinian businessmen entering Israel rose to 6,300
from 3,400, Orr said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the number of Palestinian trucks travelling
between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank, and to Jordan and Egypt,
increased to 15,178 last year from 11,962 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Orr attributed the better situation of the Palestinian economy
to the efforts made by Israel to increase the free movement of
personnels and goods despite repeated terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli coordinator listed several Israeli measures to
minimize the impact of security operations on the Palestinian
economy.
</P>
<P>
He said that Israel has decided to allow 3,000 Palestinian
workers at present to stay overnight in Israel even during time of
closure; the quota of Palestinian workers allowed to enter Israel
has remarkably been increased; and the passage of workers and
goods mainly from Gaza has been greatly simplified.
</P>
<P>
He promised that Israel would make more efforts, through
consultations with the Palestinian National Authority (PNA), to
further improve the Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
He said a better mechanism would be set up to further simplify
the passage of personnels and goods, and the number of Palestinian
workers working in Israel would also be gradually increased
despite the security risk.
</P>
<P>
Israel would also support to establish industrial parks for the
PNA, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
