<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Rift Valley Fever in Ethiopia, Says Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Minister of
Health Adem Ibrahim said Wednesday that epidemic occurrence in
the Somali and Afar regional states do not have any connection
with the rift valley fever which struck some of its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted the minister as saying that
no trace of the rift valley fever has been seen altogether in
Ethiopia so far.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the epidemic is a malaria which surfaced as
a result of the overflow of river Wabi Shebele following untimely
downpours.
</P>
<P>
Upon notification by the regional administration, he said, his
ministry dispatched health teams to places in the regional states
where the incidence of the epidemic was said to have been high
and that curative measures were also carried out.
</P>
<P>
Adem said, one team led by himself along with a representative
from the World Health Organization (WHO) visited Kebridehar,
Gode, Mustahil, Ferfer in the Somali regional state and some far
off areas in the Afar regional state.
</P>
<P>
The other noticeable health hazards are tuberculosis, measles,
dysenteryr as well as malnutrition, he said, adding that his
ministry is helping the regional states in every way possible to
put the epidemic under control.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, WHO representative Wedson Mwambazi said that the
situation is not so acute, but chronic. He pledged WHO's supports
in the efforts of the ministry to bring the epidemic under
control, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
