<HEADLINE> British Bases in Cyprus Not on War Alert: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- British military bases in
Cyprus are not on war alert due to the situation in Iraq as
reported by the local press, a spokesman for British forces in
Cyprus said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
But there was an increased number of military planes stopping
there on their way to the Gulf for the past few days, Mervyn Wynn
Jones said.
</P>
<P>
"There have been a number of extra flights passing through, on
their way to the Gulf, from a variety of places," he said.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports have said that the southern British
military base of Akrotiri and the Episkopi Garrison have been put
on war alert due to the situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jones told Cyprus News Agency that "it would be a complete
exaggeration to say that we are on war alert."
</P>
<P>
A British Defense Ministry spokesman was reported to reveal
two weeks ago that part of the personnel on the bases in Cyprus
have already been put on alert of a certain degree, due to the
situation in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"The same happens in all bases, including those in Britain
itself," he was quoted by Cypriot mass media as saying, adding
"the degree of alertness may increase according to developments."
</P>
<P>
The reports about British military bases on alert were made
following a tension in the Gulf where the U.S. has reinforced its
military presence, threatening to use force against Iraq if it
does not allow U.N. weapons inspectors to enter all sites.
</P>
<P>
Britain has retained two sovereign military bases in Cyprus
since 1960 when the island gained independence from British
colonial rule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
