<HEADLINE> Somali Commercial Ferry Capsized in Red Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A Somali commercial ferry
with more than 5,000 head of goats and its crew men is reported
to have capsized in the Red Sea last week.
</P>
<P>
The ship which sailed from the town of Berbera in northwestern
Somalia on February 3 is reported to have sunk in the Red Sea
close to the Kamaran island of Yemen.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here Wednesday said a tag boat belonging to
the Yemeni government has rushed to the rescue of the ship and
managed to save all the people aboard the vessel. Nevertheless,
all the livestock on the ferry are reported to have died.
</P>
<P>
A report said there has been no hope for the recovery of the
vessel as it sunk deep into the sea with all its livestock.
Somali businessmen have estimated the loss of the goats to more
than 300,000 U.S. Dollars, a serious economical setback for some
Somali businessmen.
</P>
<P>
This vessel is one of the dozens of ships busy in exporting
Somalia's livestock from the ports of Berbera and Bossaso to the
Arabian Gulf countries despite the ban imposed on Somalia's
animal exports to this region owing to an alleged sickness that
hit Somalia and Kenya following the disastrous floods in the past
few months.
</P>
<P>
Many Somalis and doctors deny the existence of the disease now
known as the Rift Valley Fever. The Somalis, wherever they are
including the local authorities in the self proclaimed Republic
of Somaliland, have asked for an international team to probe the
allegations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
