<HEADLINE> US Civilian Team Arrives in Jordan en Route to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A nine-member team of
U.S. civilian organization, Voice in the Wilderness arrived here
Wednesday en route to Baghdad to send medicine to Iraq in defiance
of U.N. sanctions on the country.
</P>
<P>
Over 110,000 U.S. dollars worth of medicine and medical
supplies were carried by the team for children's hospitals in
Iraq, team member Martin Thomas told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Chicago-based volunteer organization wanted to help lift as
soon as possible the economic sanctions imposed on Iraq since its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990, said team head Kathy Kelly.
</P>
<P>
"The most dramatic way (to help ease the sanctions) is that we
be there," she added.
</P>
<P>
The nine members risked 12 years in prison and a fine of 1
million dollars for carrying medicine to Iraq without
authorization, according to a press release from the team.
</P>
<P>
However, Kelly insisted that all the members had no fear so
long as their work could help ease the suffering of the Iraqi
people.
</P>
<P>
"Iraq is almost ravaged by the sanctions," said Kelly, while
showing some facts collected by her colleagues who visited the
country earlier.
</P>
<P>
She added that the sanctions were due to the U.S. who wants to
guarantee its interests in the region's oil resources.
</P>
<P>
Kelly said that her organization also condemned "any further
military strikes against the people of Iraq" and called for
"diplomatic solutions" to the current standoff between Iraq and
the U.N..
</P>
<P>
"We urge the leaders of all parties involved in the current
crisis to work toward immediate lifting of the economic sanctions
as it is the only way to solve the most pressing crisis in Iraq as
well as the suffering of the Iraqi people," the team's press
release said.
</P>
<P>
The team is scheduled to leave for Baghdad on Thursday and
they are now waiting for visas from the Iraqi Embassy in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The current trip had been the eleventh of such kind conducted
by Voice in the Wilderness since January 1996. The latest one
took place in last December when four men visited Iraq for more
than a week.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Voice in the Wilderness has dispatched more than
600,000 dollars worth of medicine and medical supplies to Baghdad
through sending teams there, said Kelly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
