<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Warns of Alarming Prospects for Children in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations official
warned here today that the prospects for children would be
alarming on the eve of the 21st century if current trends of
drying up aid continue.
</P>
<P>
The industrialized countries are far behind in their commitment
to help developing nations eradicate poverty, said Carol Bellamy,
Executive Director of the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF).
</P>
<P>
She mentioned a report made public today in Brussels by the
21-nation Development Assistance Committee (DAC) of the
Organization of Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) to
support her point of view.
</P>
<P>
The OECD report said that Official Development Assistance (ODA)
from DAC member countries totaled 55 billion US dollars in 1996, a
six percent decline over the year before. As a share of the
combined donors' Gross National Product (GNP), ODA fell to 0.25
percent in 1996, the lowest level since the UN set an ODA target
of 0.7 percent of GNP in 1970.
</P>
<P>
The figures confirm earlier findings that ODA has fallen to its
lowest levels ever, Bellamy pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"UNICEF"s analysis of the DAC numbers shows that if the current
rate of decline persists, ODA will literally vanish by the year
2015," she said. "It is hard to imagine that as an eventuality,
but that is where the numbers point."
</P>
<P>
"This is a moral issue, and a legal imperative," said the
UNICEF executive director. "Under the Convention on the Rights of
the Child, the most universally embraced human rights instrument
in history, children have a fundamental right to the fulfilment of
their basic needs."
</P>
<P>
If all donor countries had met the UN target of earmarking 0.7
percent of their GNP for development aid, Bellamy said, ODA would
exceed its current levels by 100 billion dollars a year, an amount
that, over 10 years, would be more than enough to ensure universal
access to basic social services, including health and nutrition,
education, and low-cost water supply and sanitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
