<HEADLINE> Jerusalem Police on Death of Jewish Student </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Jerusalem police suspected
that terrorism might be involved in the murder of a Jewish
religious student earlier Wednesday, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old student was stabbed on his way to a Synagogue
in the Ramat Shlomo neighborhood in northern Jerusalem at about
5:00 a.m. local time. No one witnessed the attack, only a woman
reportedly heard the shouting of the victim.
</P>
<P>
A large presence of Israeli police forces were deployed in the
area and around the city immediately after police received the
report. Roadblocks were also set up at main roads as part of the
man-hunt for the murderer.
</P>
<P>
While refraining from ruling out the possibility of criminal
act, Jerusalem police chief Yair Yithzaki and national police
Inspector-General Yehuda Wilk both said the attack seemed to be a
terrorist act.
</P>
<P>
They noted that there has been a rise in attacks against
Jewish religious students in Jerusalem recently. In last November,
a student was shot dead in the Muslim quarter of the Old City in
East Jerusalem by a suspected Palestinian militant.
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, another Jewish religious student was seriously
wounded after being stabbed by a Palestinian woman in the Old
City on his way to the West Wall to pray; last Thursday, a Jewish
student was also stabbed by an Arab attacker near the Old City;
and on Tuesday, an Israeli border patrol arrested a Palestinian
woman carrying a knife, who claimed to be on her way to carry out
an attack.
</P>
<P>
Since last November's attack, Israel has beefed up police
presence in the Old City by setting up more police stations
there.
</P>
<P>
East Jerusalem has been at the center of Israeli-Palestinian
dispute as Israel has claimed its sovereign control over the
whole city, while the Palestinians wants the occupied East
Jerusalem to be the capital of a future independent state.
</P>
<P>
Also Wednesday, a Palestinian youth was also attacked in
western Jerusalem by an unknown attacker. But police said there
was no link between the attack and the earlier incident, saying
the Palestinian man has criminal background. 
</P>
</TEXT>
