<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian, Egyptian Officials Discuss Iraqi Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Egypt Wednesday
underlined the need for a continued diplomatic effort to avert a
possible U.S. attack on Iraq, the Iranian official news agency
IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
In a telephone consultation, Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi and his Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa discussed the
latest developments of the crisis over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
Both of them called on Iraq to observe and implement the U.N.
Security Council resolutions, the IRNA said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was triggered by Iraq's denial of access to the
United Nations arms inspectors charged with eliminating its
weapons of mass destruction to 68 sites, including presidential
palaces.
</P>
<P>
The United States is strengthening military build-up in the
Gulf and says it will attack Iraq to force its compliance with the
arms inspections if international efforts fail to achieve positive
results.
</P>
<P>
In their discussion, Kharrazi and Moussa reviewed the mediation
made by Russia, France and the Arab League, and their proposals
aimed at defusing the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has reportedly proposed jointly with the three parties
that eight presidential palaces be inspected by a special group,
whose members should include those from the five permanent members
of the U.N. Security Council - France, Russia, China, the U.S. and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad Saeed el-Sahhaf reportedly said
Wednesday in Cairo after a meeting with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak that "when we say eight (presidential palaces) we are
actually talking about all the sites" in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
