<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Reduce Trade Barriers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) has agreed to implement the COMESA
customs bond guarantee scheme to reduce major costs to shippers,
exporters and importers in a bid to reduce trade barriers in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The scheme is required for transit goods to ensure customs
duties and taxes are recovered by the government of the transit
country in the event of goods being illegally sold within its
territory, according to a statement released here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It said the current scheme provides that customs guarantees
are arranged in a country where the supplier is resident, unlike
the cumbersome old system where customs bond guarantees for
transit traffic had to be deposited in each transit country.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA customs bond guarantee will enhance the
competitiveness of goods traded within and outside the region
because the costs required by customs transit bonds will be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
The program is expected to be implemented no later than
October 1, this year, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The cost of documentation is also expected to be reduced by
about 15 to 20 percent and customs cooperation is expected to be
enhanced among its 20 member states, the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA transit trade facilitation program comprises among
others the COMESA yellow card, COMESA carriers license,
harmonized road transit charges and COMESA transit plates.
</P>
<P>
Namibia, Tanzania and Zimbabwe have implemented the COMESA
customs document while other member countries are in the process
of introducing the document. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
