<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Monetary Policy Is Now Finely Balanced: Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Record-breaking price
reductions during the New Year sales in Britain sent the cost of
living plunging last month, enabling the Government to hit its 2.5
percent inflation target.
</P>
<P>
The scale of the price discounts in the sales brought the
underlying measure of inflation down to the target for the first
time since the Labor came to power last May.
</P>
<P>
The drop in the price of clothing and footwear last month was
the biggest since 1947, while the price of house-hold goods such
as fridges and furniture recorded the biggest fall since
comparable records began in 1956.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the figures, the Bank of England said on
Wednesday that the UK's monetary policy is now more finely
balanced than at any time over the past five years with output
rising at 3 percent a year and inflation has fallen from 5 percent
to 2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
But the Bank, which has the power to decide rate, dashed market
hopes that interest rates have peaked by adding the balance of
inflation risks remain to the upside.
</P>
<P>
The Bank said there were a number of inflationary risks -- a
more rapid fall in the exchange rate than that implied by interest
rate differentials, past rapid money growth and, particularly,
pressures in the labor market.
</P>
<P>
It also said, monetary policy is being pulled in opposite
directions. On the one hand, the impact of the rise in sterling on
both exports and imports is likely to slow growth sharply over the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, inflation is, at present, temporarily
depressed by the one-off fall in import prices which is masking a
level of domestically generated inflation of over 3 percent,
significantly above the target level.
</P>
<P>
But earnings growth remained at 4.75 percent overall, and
according to the Bank's estimates, over 5 percent in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
So the Bank warned that earnings growth, especially in the
private sector, will have to fall back if the inflation target is
to be met.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
