<HEADLINE> UK Pledged to Act on N.Irish Killings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- British Northern Ireland
Secretary Mo Mowlam vowed Wednesday to take immediate action if
there was proof any party at the peace talks was connected to two
killings in the province this week.
</P>
<P>
"The government will not hesitate to act if it is deemed that
any party has dishonored the Mitchell Principles," Mowlam told
parliament, referring to the code of non-violence binding
participants in the talks.
</P>
<P>
"There is a great deal of speculation about who is responsible,
but it has not yet been established what happened," Mowlam said.
"When the RUC (police) and the Chief Constable come to me with the
facts, we will act."
</P>
<P>
No group has claimed responsibility for the latest two killings
and the police have not commented on speculation that three men
they have arrested are linked to Irish Republican Army guerrillas
fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
After the two killings over the last 24 hours, seven IRA
suspects were questioned in connection with one of the murders,
local reports said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, pro-British Ulster Unionist leader David
Trimble called for the expulsion of Sinn Fein, the political wing
of the IRA, from the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
All parties in Northern Ireland are required under the Mitchell
Principles, named after talks chairman George Mitchell, to commit
themselves exclusively to peaceful and democratic means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
