<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Mixed, Paris Hits New Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Share prices in Europe's major
stock markets ended mixed Wednesday, with London slightly down
and Paris surging to another record closing high.
</P>
<P>
Leading British shares in London slipped back into negative
territory as the market tracked a dull showing on Wall Street,
with the FTSE 100 index closing down 5.4 points at 5,607.9 points.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Bank of England's latest quarterly inflation
report which was published Wednesday hinted at another rate hike
to come.
</P>
<P>
It said the risk of inflation is on the increase and the era of
high growth and falling inflation is probably over.
</P>
<P>
The market was led higher by pharmaceutical stocks, but was
dragged down by bank sectors which gave up recent gains and by oil
stocks which fell over fears of lower crude prices.
</P>
<P>
The CAC-40 index in Paris closed only 4.24 points up at
3,240.00, but hit another record high, giving up earlier strong
gains as Wall Street failed to build on Tuesday's record close.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that declines in banking and oil stocks also
pulled the market back.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the DAX-30 index ended the session 64.68 points
higher at 4,588.43, as share prices held firm in late trade thanks
to the stronger dollar and Wall Street's overnight record close.
</P>
</TEXT>
