<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Demands "Full and Free" Access by Inspectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton
insisted Wednesday that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein must give
U.N. inspectors "full and free" access to suspected weapons sites
in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"He must let the weapons inspectors back with full and free
access to all suspected sites. If he will not act, we must be
prepared to do so," Clinton said in a speech at the U.S. State
Department.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz earlier Wednesday
offered to open eight "presidential sites" for inspection under
the supervision of representatives of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Before Clinton's remarks on the Iraqi offer, White House
spokesman Mike McCurry said, "The U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM)
needs free and unfettered access to those sites that it needs to
investigate to determine what capacity Iraq has or could have to
weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
"It was not up to Iraq to set the conditions for those
inspections. I's up to the United Nations to do the work as the
United Nations sees fit," McCurry told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The United States is determined to force Iraq to abide by the
U.N. resolutions on weapons inspections and has repeated its stand
that if diplomacy failed, it would mount an air strike against
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We all hope we can avoid the use of force, but let's face it,
in the end that is up to Saddam Hussein," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
The United States has already assembled a mighty force in the
Gulf, which has also been augmented by British ships and
warplanes, for a possible attack on Iraq once the diplomacy
engaged by the international community failed.
</P>
<P>
Anthony Zinni, the commander of the U.S. force in the Middle
East said earlier Wednesday that Washington would be ready to
strike Iraq within about a week.
</P>
<P>
"I would say we're within a week or so," he said in the final
hours of a three-day tour of the Gulf with U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
"We're ready now but there are a few more pieces to put in,"
Zinni said. "My biggest concern would be to ensure we have looked
at every possible reaction to a strike and we have sufficient...
plan to handle anything that might come up." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
