<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dredging of Dar Harbor Near Completion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The dredging of Dar es
Salaam harbor which started in mid-1997 is expected to be
completed by April, Samson Luhigo, director general of Tanzania
Harbor Authority (THA), told reporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Luhigo said the progress made by three vessels in dredging up
the entrance to the harbor is "impressing."
</P>
<P>
Widening of harbor entrance will resolve the problem of tide
movement which hold sway over the performance of containers, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, during the period of tide ebb, a
container whose cargo has already been unloaded may have to wait
because of the limited depth of the harbor.
</P>
<P>
The vessel has blocked the way for others to enter for
discharge of cargo, affecting the handling capacity of the
harbor, the official said.
</P>
<P>
When the 23-million-US-Dollar project is completed, vessels of
up to 40,000 tons will be able to enter the harbor.
</P>
<P>
The project is being carried out by a Dutch firm HAM, with the
Dutch government meeting some 60 percent of the project's cost
while the rest is to be financed by the Tanzanian government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
