<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Herbal Drugs Fight AIDS (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists plan to
conduct clinical research to determine the effectiveness of an
herbal compound for treating acquired immune deficiency syndrome
(AIDS).
</P>
<P>
The preparation, a powder, consists of bupleurum, milkvetch,
Chinese angelica and licorice which dissipate heat and toxic
materials, while improving human immune functions, according to
Doctor Wang Jian from the Chinese Academy of Traditional Chinese
Medicine (TCM). Wang is a member of a Sino-Tanzanian research
group working on the new AIDS drug.
</P>
<P>
Pending formal approval, Wang and his colleagues, both Chinese
and Tanzanian, will monitor levels of HIV - the AIDS virus - in
patients following the application of medication.
</P>
<P>
The research will also focus on changing quantities of CD4
positive cells and neopterin, two leading indications of human
immuno function.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to achieve reliable and convincing results on the
effectiveness of the medication," said Wang. He stressed that
major criteria for appraising curative effects has been adopted
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
The scientists will introduce AZT, a common anti-HIV drug, in a
control group to provide a comparison.
</P>
<P>
"Research on AIDS treatment with herbal therapies was launched
more than ten years ago. However, Western medical circles failed
to recognize verified results owing to different appraisal
criteria," said Wang.
</P>
<P>
"Bearing these facts in mind, we must introduce the
aforementioned criteria," according to Professor Guan Chongfen, a
veteran researcher in AIDS treatment integrated with TCM
methods. She said that results of the clinical research and
immunological methods over the past 10 years prove that TCM has a
40-50 percent effective rate in the treatment of AIDS.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Calls for Turco-Greek Meeting to Solve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has proposed that a
high-level Turkish-Greek meeting be held to solve their disputes
over the Aegean Sea, an official statement said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statement, issued by Turkish Foreign Ministry, said that
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem had presented a verbal note
to the Greek ambassador in Ankara to make the peace proposal.
</P>
<P>
"The response of Greece to this initiative will display and
prove the good will of both countries in the eyes of the
international community," it quoted Cem as saying.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the U.S.-initiated "Madrid Declaration"
and the "Confidence Building Measures in the Aegean" proposed by
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) will help improve
the Turco-Greek relationship.
</P>
<P>
They call on Turkey and Greece to avoid military confrontation
and settle their problems over the Aegean and Cyprus issue
through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
Turkey suggests that a high-level meeting between the two
foreign ministries should be held in Ankara or Athens before the
end of March, 1998, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Spokesman of Turkish Foreign Ministry Sermet Atacanli
told Xinhua by telephone that Turkey prefers to increasing
bilateral contacts to narrow the gap between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, two traditional rivals, have long been at
odds over a series of issues, including the airspace limits,
mineral rights under the Aegean Sea as well as the thorny Cyprus
question.
</P>
<P>
Warplanes and naval vessels from the two countries, both NATO
members, are often involved in minor clashes over and in the
Aegean Sea, triggering endless accusations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Herbal Drugs Fight AIDS (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to an agreement between the Chinese and Tanzanian
governments, scientists at the Chinese Academy of TCM have used
herbal medicine, including Tokyo violet and milkvetch, to treat
approximately 10,000 Tanzanian AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
"We've recorded a 47 percent effective rate in improving human
immuno functions and various AIDS symptoms, including asthenia,
diarrhea, fever, leanness and skin rash," according to Guan.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Chinese scientists, researchers from Hong Kong, the
United States and Japan have also recorded noticeable progress in
reconstituting curative compounds from herbs, said Guan.
</P>
<P>
Compounds extracted from Tokyo violet, snake gourd root,
liquorice and alkaloid lighten the symptoms of HIV. Balsam pear
and scutellaria also increase T4 cells, while milkvetch and
various edible fungi improve human immune functions.
</P>
<P>
"When compared with Western medical treatment which focuses
more on attacking HIV, TCM emphasizes improving the patient's
immunity in order to block the virus," according to the professor.
</P>
<P>
"Moreover, TCM compounds have fewer side effects, and are more
affordable than chemical-based drugs. Advances in TCM research
will be good news for AIDS patients," said Guan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
