<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Government Opens Internet Homepage for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The German government announced
Thursday that it has opened a special Internet homepage, called
the "Youngnet", to offer convenient information services to young
people between 16 and 26 years old.
</P>
<P>
According to German government spokesman Peter Hausmann, the
Youngnet will serve as a user-friendly platform to gather and
provide useful information available on the Internet for the young
people.
</P>
<P>
Programs offered by the Youngnet include job introduction,
education, science, political information and entertainment. It
would also allow young people to participate in on-line discussion
forums, to chat with prominent figures or to make use of the
E-Mail-Service to send post worldwide free of charge.
</P>
<P>
"Under the framework of the Youngnet, we are offering the
positive side of the Internet in all aspects," said Hausmann.
</P>
<P>
The Youngnet also has a young editorial group which knows the
special interests of young people and would ensure a better
communication with them.
</P>
<P>
According to Hausmann, the German government has invested
500,000 marks (about 275,000 U.S. dollars) on the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
