<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Ambassador: Iraqi Proposal Positive, Not </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, February 12 (Xinhua) -- French Ambassador to Jordan
Thursday described as "positive" but "not enough" Wednesday's
proposal by Iraqi foreign minister to open altogether 68 suspected
sites to international arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
It was a "step forward" that Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammed
Saeed al-Sahhaf made such a proposal in Cairo, Egypt, to open all
the sites allegedly holding prohibited weapons, said Bernard
Pajolete during an interview with official Radio Jordan.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iraqi offer was "not enough" as it restricted the
appointment of weapons inspectors to U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan and limited the possibility of repeated inspections on the
presidential sites, Pajolete added.
</P>
<P>
France insisted that Iraq should act fully in accordance with
U.N. resolutions and let inspectors enter all the suspected sites
without any preconditions because only little time was left for
diplomatic efforts, the French ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
Pajolete warned Iraq that "Time is running out." The United
States has threatened to launch military actions against Iraq in a
week or so to make it comply with all the demands of the arms
inspectors under the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
Paris also asked Annan to put forward his own ideas on the
basis of French and Russian initiatives and pay a visit to
Baghdad as soon as possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
Since Annan had not traveled to Iraq yet, France believed that
diplomatic solution had not been exhausted, said Pajolete.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ambassador said that his country was still
continuing contacts with all parties concerned to find a peaceful
solution to the Iraqi-U.N. standoff caused by Baghdad's
prevention of the UNSCOM inspectors from entering some suspected
sites.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine had recently phoned
Annan, his Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov as well as Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz to discuss the latest
developments, Pajolete added.
</P>
<P>
France earlier submitted a proposal called "Qualitative
Formula," which means that the arms inspectors from the UNSCOM
can enter the surroundings of the presidential palaces, such as
the gardens; but they are not allowed to enter the residence
area, such as the bedrooms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
