<HEADLINE> Spain's Moron Base on Standby for Possible Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Spain's military base at Moron
is already on standby for a possible U.S. strike against Iraq,
Spanish government sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
If no diplomatic solution is found to the crisis over the
United Nations weapons inspections and the United States decides
to launch a military attack against Iraq, Spain will offer the
Moron base to support U.S. operations, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
As early as in November 1997, when the crisis began, the
Spanish government declared that it would authorize the use of its
military bases by U.S. forces as long as the latter pose the
demand.
</P>
<P>
Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar reiterated on Wednesday
his government's stance that Spain would "be on the side of the
allies" in case of an attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The El Paris newspaper said Tuesday that Spain had already
given the United States the authorization to use its Moron base in
the southern Andalusia region.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted government sources as saying that the United
States hoped to put 30 tanker aircraft at the base for in-flight
refueling of aircraft.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. general has left to inspect the base.
</P>
<P>
Spain was a strategically important staging ground for the
U.S.-led attacks on Iraq during the 1991 Gulf War, and Moron was
one of the bases used then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
