<HEADLINE> Tokyo Urges Baghdad to Accept U.N. Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan urged Iraq on Thursday to
accept unconditional and full United Nations weapons inspections
to avoid a U.S.-led military strike, Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi summoned Muhsin Ali,
charge d'affaires at the Iraqi embassy in Tokyo, on Thursday and
expressed Japan's "grave concerns" over the issue, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was quoted as telling Ali that Japan wants to see Iraq
complying with U.N. resolutions and fully cooperating with
inspectors of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM).
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Obuchi asked Chinese Ambassador Xu Dunxin
to help find a diplomatic solution to Washington's confrontation
with Iraq over its refusal to allow U.N. weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi told Xu that Japan hopes to resolve the Iraq crisis
through diplomatic means and that Iraq's unconditional acceptance
of U.N. inspections is essential for a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Xu said China also considers Iraq's acceptance
of the inspections vital, but does not support the use of force
because it would complicate rather than resolve the problem.
</P>
