<HEADLINE> HK Strategic Development Commission Meets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The newly-established
Commission on Strategic Development of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) held its first meeting Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa later told reporters that members
of the commission had "a very useful exchange of views" during the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of the commission is to take a long term look at
how Hong Kong is to move forward, how we are going to be able to
maintain our economic vitality, and how we are going to maintain
our competitiveness," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We paid particular attention to our major overseas partners as
to how they are moving in the longer term and what are their
trends," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Additionally, we will be looking closely at how to work with
our own country, China's mainland, in economic, industrial and
commercial sectors to enhance each other's competitiveness and to
improve our benefit for each other," Tung stressed.
</P>
<P>
A government spokesman told reporters that a team of
consultants will be engaged to draw up and assess long term
scenarios for deliberation by the commission.
</P>
<P>
In coordination with the work of the commission, relevant
policy bureaus will conduct studies on individual policy areas,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Long term development strategies or policies arising from these
studies will be submitted to the Executive Council, he added.
</P>
<P>
Members of the commission will meet once every six to eight
weeks.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's meeting followed the appointment of the commission
members by Tung on January 16.
</P>
<P>
The commission is led by the chief executive and composed of
Administrative Secretary Anson Chan, Financial Secretary Donald
Tsang, and well-known businessmen and scholars in Hong Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
