<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR -- Mongolia exported 350 barrels of crude oil to
China Wednesday, thus turning a new page on its oil exportation.
</P>
<P>
A grand ceremony was held at the Tamsag oil field, located in
Dornod Aimak. Mongolian Prime Minister Mendsaikhan Enkhsaikhan
attended the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The oil was transported to China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region by trucks. Reports said that 360 barrels of oil produced
from the field will be exported every day to China later on.
(Mongolia-China-Oil)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan and Poland agreed Thursday to abolish visas for
the two countries' nationals visiting each other's countries in a
bid to promote bilateral exchanges, Kyodo News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a meeting between Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and visiting Polish President
Aleksander Kwasniewski.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which is expected to be put into force in
April, travelers and businessmen of the two countries will be
allowed to stay in each other's countries for as long as three
months if they do not intend to engage in work, said government
officials. (Japan-Poland-Visa Abolition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Asia is not the entire focus of Boeing, which is
eyeing Europe and other markets for its jets, an official of the
Seattle manufacturer said recently.
</P>
<P>
Tim Meskill, Boeing's market outlook manager, said that the
company has many options in the face of delayed orders from Asian
airlines.
</P>
<P>
Europe, where air traffic increased a surprising 10 percent
last year, seems to be Boeing's first market alternative.
</P>
<P>
Boeing expects the total number of its planes order in 1998 to
be near the 502 booked last year. Most will have to come from
outside Asia, earlier seen as the leading market.
(US-Boeing-Markets)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- The Seoul Municipality announced Thursday its
decision, effective next Friday, to raise taxi fares by an average
of 23.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The basic fee for entering a taxi will grow from the current
1,000 won (about 0.70 U.S. dollar) to 1,300 won (0.91 dollar).
</P>
<P>
The municipal government attributed the rise to the fuel prices
hike -- up nearly 100 percent since late last year -- which are
caused by the country's current financial crisis. (SKorea-Taxi
Fares)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
