<HEADLINE> Guangdong Tightens Border Inspections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 12 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
Province has strengthened its quarantine system for fresh
vegetables and live poultry bound for Hong Kong, according to
local officials.
</P>
<P>
The Guangdong Provincial Administration for the Inspection of
Import and Export Commodities is empowered to inspect all local
shipments of live animals bound for the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), according to Administrator Li Jun.
</P>
<P>
A total of 168 vegetable production bases approved by the
administration ship more than 20,000 tons of fresh vegetables to
the Hong Kong SAR on a monthly basis. A contingent of quality
inspectors have been trained to monitor pesticide levels at the
bases.
</P>
<P>
All shipments of live poultry must have both quarantine and
quality inspection certificates.
</P>
<P>
The administration guarantees that poultry is free of the bird
flu virus and various other infectious viruses, according to
officials. 
</P>
