<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Conference on Arsenic Pollution Ends in Dhaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A 4-day international conference
on arsenic pollution of ground water concluded here Thursday with
the adoption of The Dhaka Declaration.
</P>
<P>
Over 280 scientists from 17 countries and regions in the field
have come to the understanding that "the ground water of a
significantly large area in Bangladesh is contaminated with high
concentration of arsenic; the cause of this arsenic contamination
is geological," the declaration stated.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out, "A large number of people including children
are suffering from chronic arsenic poisoning," and "the arsenic
problem is a threat to public health and the social structure of
Bangladesh."
</P>
<P>
Supply of arsenic-free water is the only solution to the
problem, the declaration said.
</P>
<P>
"The arsenic contamination of ground water in Bangladesh needs
to be addressed on an emergency basis," it stressed.
</P>
<P>
The conference participants agreed "to share information among
themselves, make their findings freely accessible and allow others
to use them for the interest of all people," it said.
</P>
<P>
"We shall assist in the setting up of organizations and centers
for research, training, storage and dissemination of information
relating to mitigation of the arsenic problem in Bangladesh and
all over the world," the declaration concluded.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh suffers most seriously from arsenic pollution in the
world. Fifty-two districts out of a total of 64 with a population
of 76.9 million, have been polluted. The Bangladeshi government
has taken a series of measures to control arsenic contamination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
