<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Constitutional Convention Favors Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian Constitutional
Convention Thursday came down behind a republic, choosing a
proposal to appoint a president of the republic by a two-thirds
majority of both houses of federal parliament.
</P>
<P>
On the ninth day of the Constitutional Convention, the 151
delegates present made it clear they want a referendum and they
want parliament to endorse the appointment of president.
</P>
<P>
Now the republicans have only one obstacle to overcome to
ensure a referendum on the republic next year -- Prime Minister
John Howard.
</P>
<P>
When the convention opened almost two weeks ago, Howard said he
would accept the "clear view" of the convention when deciding
whether to call a referendum or put the republic issue off to a
non-binding national vote.
</P>
<P>
The final votes will be taken Friday, when delegates decide
whether to become a republic and whether to set a referendum in
train.
</P>
<P>
On the initial votes Thursday, the convention voted 75 to 71 to
endorse the Australian Republican Movement (ARM) plan as the best
model for a republic, with four delegates abstaining and two
monarchists absent.
</P>
<P>
That vote suggests the outcome Friday would be close.
</P>
<P>
Republicans would be more concerned about the stand taken by
four state Labor Opposition leaders - Queensland's Peter Beattie,
Western Australia's Geoff Gallop, South Australia's Mike Rann and
Tasmania's Jim Bacon.
</P>
<P>
At a joint media conference, they declared they would now vote
for the ARM model but would continue to campaign for a direct
election of president.
</P>
<P>
Their comments are a worrying sign for the referendum campaign.
Monarchists will be able to argue that the republicans remain
divided and the republic system may be changed within a few years.
</P>
<P>
The Labor leaders also proved that while the numbers favor a
republic, divisions remain on how it should be done.
</P>
<P>
Republicans will also be concerned about how Prime Minister
Howard will interpret their stand and whether he will consider the
final numbers really represent the convention's "clear view".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
