<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines, EU to Expand Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and the
European Union (EU) are keen on expanding their trade and
investment by 20 percent in 1998 by further improving the
standards and quality of their tradable goods.
</P>
<P>
This is the goal of the 146.4 million pesos (3.7 million U.S.
dollars) European Commission-Philippines Economic Cooperation
Program on Standards, Quality and Conformity Assessment which will
be implemented by the two sides in the next three years.
</P>
<P>
A memorandum of understanding (MOU) on the program was signed
Thursday by Trade Secretary Cesar Bautista and EU delegation head
Candido Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said that the EU and the Philippines have recognized
the need to continue the program on the basis of the result of a
former program which was introduced in 1989.
</P>
<P>
"As Philippine exports to Europe are growing in quality and
volume, creating technical conditions for locally-made products is
necessary," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rodriguez said this will not only mean opening the market to
the Philippines but also will put this country in a competitive
position.
</P>
<P>
Bautista said the two countries are determined to remove
unnecessary barriers, such as non-conformance of goods to
international standards, to improve their trade and investments
link.
</P>
<P>
He said the program is expected to strengthen the quality and
infrastructure and encourage the exchange of good quality
practices between economic sectors of the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
