<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Washington Blamed for Double Standard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 12 (Xinhua) - An Iranian daily Thursday
blamed the United States for its double-standard policy towards
arms inspection, by rejecting Iranian and Cuban arms inspectors
visiting U.S. chemical weapons facilities.
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the U.S. is going to wage another devastating war
against Iraq because of Baghdad's demand to exclude American
inspectors from the U.N. Special Commission on disarmament
(UNSCOM) while Washington itself rejected Iranian and Cuban arms
inspectors to visit U.S. facilities, Tehran Times quoted an
unnamed "analyst" as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons
decided to employ about 126 inspectors to probe signatory
countries, but the U.S. announced that Iranian and Cuban
nationals should be excluded from the list of the U.N. arms
inspection team to visit U.S. chemical facilities.
</P>
<P>
"It is a clear example of double standard on the part
of the United States," the Iranian analyst said, adding that
the U.S. has waged a devastating war against Iraq (in 1991)
and for about seven years the U.S.-dominated UNSCOM in a
combing operation has been inspecting each and every inch of
the Iraqi territory.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqis had every reason to be suspicious about the
unusual prolongation of the UNSCOM operations, he said,
therefore, their demand for the expulsion of American inspectors
from the UNSCOM was quite natural.
</P>
<P>
The latest Iraqi crisis, over which the U.S. is threatening
to carry out military attack, stemmed from Baghdad's demand to
change the composition of the U.N. inspection team, (exactly
what the U.S. is doing,) the daily noted.
</P>
<P>
Despite of the strong worldwide opposition, the U. S. and
Britain have been building up their military deployment in the
Gulf preparing a military attack on Iraq following its standoff
with the U.N. over arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
Although Iraq has promised to open the eight suspected
presidential palaces to the U.N. arms inspectors, Washington and
London insisted that Baghdad should allow "unconditional and
unrestricted" arms inspection of the U.N. teams in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
