<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
Riyadh -- Director General of Saudi Arabia's Arab Investment
Company Saleh Al-Homaidan has announced that the company managed
to achieve good financial results in 1997, as its net profits
amounted to 58 million U.S. dollars, 28 million more than that of
1996.
</P>
<P>
Homaidan attributed the rise in the company's profits to the
selling of the shares of its two banking projects, namely,
Tunisia's National Economic Development Bank and Egypt's
Commercial International bank.
</P>
<P>
Cairo -- Egyptian Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili
declared that the Egyptian-Saudi High Commission would meet next
April in Cairo to discuss the executive steps peculiar to the
establishment of a joint free-trade zone, as well as ways of
promoting economic trade and investment ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Tehran -- Board Chairman of the "Iran Khordru" company
Menushahr Gharwi, the biggest and the oldest automobile
manufacturer in Iran, announced that Iran would invest 1 billion
U.S. dollars in developing the national automobile industry in the
coming three years.
</P>
<P>
He added that this is designed to enable the company to produce
250,000 vehicles a year, 140,000 more than the production at
present. The company, a main partner of the Peugeot company of
France, currently produce Peugeot 405's.
</P>
<P>
Jerusalem -- Foreign investments in Israel rose by 44 percent
last year to stand at 3.9 billion dollars, despite the deadlock in
the Middle East peace process, an official source has said.
</P>
<P>
The investments were mainly devoted to high-tech
enterprises. Direct foreign contributions to the investments of
Israeli institutions amounted to 1.8 billion U.S. dollars,
compared to 1.3 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Economy Youssef Butros Ghali has
announced that Egypt plans to amend the laws restricting the
movement of foreign investments in the insurance sector.
</P>
<P>
He added that none of the national insurance companies would
be sold, but the door will be opened for foreign investment
to establish new insurance companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
