<HEADLINE> Soeharto Orders Armed Forces to Act Sternly Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President Soeharto
here Thursday ordered the armed forces to take stern action
against anyone caught doing an unconstitutional act that could
lead to the nation's disintegration.
</P>
<P>
"We are all concerned over the undemocratic acts of small
groups which claim to be upholders of democracy," the president
said when receiving military officers attending the leadership
meeting of the Indonesian Armed Forces (ABRI).
</P>
<P>
Aside from taking stern measures against those who will disturb
the upcoming general session of the People's Consultative Assembly
(MPR), the military should also create a peaceful situation during
the March 1-11 session, official Antara News Agency quoted the
president as saying.
</P>
<P>
"You (the military) must carry out security measures during the
MPR assembly properly. There is no need for you to overreact, just
be alert," Soeharto, who is also commander-in-chief of the ABRI,
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that unconstitutional groups, which have been trying to
use the protracted monetary crisis to undermine the government,
should not be allowed to exist.
</P>
<P>
Rumors are circulating around the country as tension mounts
prior to the indirect presidential elections next month, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The economic crisis has yet to be overcome. The prices of
essential commodities are soaring. Companies are forced to reduce
activities or even close down," he said. All this paved the way
for certain groups to use the situation to achieve political goals
which they cannot reach through democratic and constitutional
means. 
</P>
</TEXT>
