<HEADLINE> Ramos Orders Thorough Probe of Philippine Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- President Fidel Ramos Thursday
ordered a thorough investigation of the DC-9 air tragedy last week
during which all 104 aboard the plane were killed.
</P>
<P>
"We must get to the bottom of this (plane crash)," Ramos told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Ramos said he would like to know the truth of what really
happened when the Cebu Air Pacific DC-9 plane went down in heavily
forested Mount Sumagaya in the southern province of Misamis
Oriental on February 2.
</P>
<P>
All the l04 people on board -- 99 passengers and five crewmen
-- perished in the country's worst aviation crash.
</P>
<P>
Ramos' order came after the Air Transportation Office (ATO) and
the Civil Aeronautic Board (CAB) accused each other of being
responsible for approving a diverted flight plan of the ill-fated
plane.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft made an unscheduled stopover at Tacloban city
instead of going straight to Cagayan de Oro city in Misamis
Oriental from Manila. The side trip was believed to be the cause
of the crash as it forced the pilot to negotiate an unfamiliar
route.
</P>
<P>
Ramos ordered officials of the ATO and the CAB to stop
finger-pointing at this stage while investigation is in progress.
</P>
<P>
Ten days after the crash happened, rescue operations are still
going on to search for bodies of the victims and the wreckage of
the aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Rescue operations have been slow as the bodies were blown up to
pieces and thrown several kilometers away from the crash site. So
far, rescuers have retrieved about 90 bags of body parts.
</P>
<P>
The "black box", the flight data recorder which will provide
clues to the cause of the crash, has been recovered and brought to
Canada for evaluation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
