<HEADLINE> E. Guinea Denies Massacre of Nigerians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Equatorial Guinean officials in
Nigeria has denied reports of an indiscriminate killing of
Nigerians living in that country, but confirmed that three
Nigerians are in detention in connection with an alleged coup
plot.
</P>
<P>
Juan Antonio Bibang Nchuchuma, E.Guinea's consul-general
in Calabar, capital of the Cross River State in southeast Nigeria,
said Wednesday that there is no such a massacre as alleged by
some Nigerians returning from E. Guinea recently.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian media Tuesday quoted them as saying that some 700
Nigerians have been killed and many more put into jails in what
seems like a witch hunt against Nigerians after the failed coup
plot.
</P>
<P>
The consul-general confirmed that three retired Nigerian army
officers are currently detained in connection with the alleged
coup plot.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the officers were contracted by an E.
Guinean dissidents group which had been plotting to overthrow the
government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, media reports said Thursday that some 100 Nigerians
newly fled from E. Guinea besieged the government of the Cross
River State Wednesday, demanding that the government take urgent
actions to evacuate and protect Nigerians in E. Guinea. 
</P>
</TEXT>
