<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosperity of HK Port to Continue: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- "Hong Kong has always lived
with change and challenge, and with careful planning we can look
forward to an era of continuing prosperity for the port of Hong
Kong," said Chairman of the Port Development Board Peter Thompson.
</P>
<P>
In the foreword of the newly-published 1996-97 annual report of
the board, Thompson said, "We are now firmly established as the
new Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of the People's
Republic of China," and was confident that "the new era will open
up new and challenging opportunities for the port, both now and
well into the next century."
</P>
<P>
The board advises the government on port development. Hong Kong
is the only major port in the world that doesn't have a port
authority and is run by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Thompson noted that one of the most significant developments in
1996-97 was the decision to move ahead with Container Terminal 9
(CT9). The agreement reached among the parties selected to build
and operate the new terminal included a program to rationalize the
ownership of the existing berths of Container Terminus 1 to 8.
</P>
<P>
"The rationalization program, together with the completion of
CT9 in the early 2000s, will expand substantially the handling
capacity of the Kwai Chung container port by over 2.6 million TEUs
(Twenty-foot Equivalent Units)," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The new facilities and larger handling capacity will better
enable the terminal operators to handle the new generation of
larger container vessels, and to meet the needs of the shipping
alliances, he said.
</P>
<P>
The port handled 14.5 million TEUs of containers in 1997,
maintaining its position as the world's busiest container port for
six years in a row. The container port throughput is forecast to
increase by 7 percent, reaching 15.5 million TEUs in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Thompson added that work continued on both the new River Trade
Terminal at Tuen Men and the Permanent Mid-stream Facility at
Stonecutters Island. Both facilities are due to come into
operation in 1998.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong is thus well equipped with these different modes of
container-handling to move into the next century and to handle the
ever-increasing volume of containers moving through our port," he
commented.
</P>
<P>
The River Trade Terminal in particular is a new concept to
develop the Pearl River Delta waterways as the water highways for
carrying containers between Hong Kong and the many delta ports in
southern China, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
