<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Opposition Party Leader Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A group of old guard members
of the United National Party (UNP), the main opposition party in
Sri Lanka, have been alleged to plan a coup to oust its leader
Ranil Wickremasinghe, the national news agency Lankapuvath
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Lankapuvath quoted political sources as saying that most of the
members in the group are those who had carried out acts of murder,
bribery and corruption during the 17-year UNP regime. The UNP was
defeated by the People's Alliance in the 1994 general elections.
</P>
<P>
They have already launched an open campaign against
Wickremasinghe's leadership, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Fearing they would be punished by law, they formed a survival
group to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, among the group are a number of
former parliamentarians, former arms dealers and businessmen
engaged in illegal activities. They had made millions of rupees
(62 Sri Lankan rupees to one U.S. dollar at current rate) through
corruption, the news agency added.
</P>
<P>
It said that as a last resort to save themselves and return to
power by hook or by crook, they launched the campaign to seek the
support of former UNP strongman Sirisena Cooray and planned to
replace Wickremasinghe with Cooray.
</P>
<P>
So far the UNP is not available for comment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
