<HEADLINE> Chinese President Meets With U.S. Religious Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said here today that he welcomes friends from the U.S. religious
circle to visit China.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with three visiting American religious
leaders, Jiang said that U.S. clergy could see for themselves what
is happening in China and hear about the ideas and views of the
people from all walks of life, especially in the religious
community. The U.S. clergy then could relate what they have seen
and heard to the U.S. public to improve the mutual understanding
between the people of the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The three U.S. clergymen were Rabbi Arthur Schneier, president
of the Appeal of Conscience Foundation; Archbishop Theodore
McCarrick of the Newark Roman Catholic Archdiocese; and Reverend
Don Argue, president of the National Association of
Evangelicals. They and their delegation are visiting China as
guest of the Chinese People's Institute of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Jiang recalled his state visit to the United States last October
and said it had promoted the development of Sino-U.S. ties and
improved mutual understanding between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States share extensive common interests,
though they have differences on some issues, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
The lack of mutual understanding is one of the major
factors resulting in the differences, Jiang said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the only correct way of narrowing or
even eliminating the differences is to expand bilateral
exchanges, enhance mutual understanding and seek common
ground while preserving divergences on the basis of equality and
mutual respect.
</P>
<P>
The American religious leaders said that President Jiang's
U.S. tour had greatly promoted the Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
They told Jiang that the purpose of their ongoing China trip is
to increase the exchange between the religious circles of the two
countries, enhance the mutual understanding and friendship between
the American and Chinese peoples, and further promote
theimprovement and development the Sino-U.S. ties.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. clergymen said they are ready to build a bridge for
the U.S.-China dialogue and exchanges together with their Chinese
counterparts and personnel from other sectors.
</P>
<P>
The American visitors are also scheduled to visit Nanjing,
Shanghai and Lhasa, in addition to Beijing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
