<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seoul to Raise Taxi Fares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Seoul Municipality announced
Thursday its decision, effective next Friday, to raise taxi fares
by an average of 23.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The basic fee for entering a taxi will grow from the current
1,000 won (about 0.70 U.S. dollar) to 1,300 won (0.91 dollar).
</P>
<P>
The municipal government attributed the rise to the fuel prices
hike -- up nearly 100 percent since late last year -- which are
caused by the country's current financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two months, the Seoul Municipality has raised the
fares of buses and subway while the country has increased those of
domestic and international flight.
</P>
<P>
Since late 1997, South Korean won has dipped deep down against
the dollar as the nation faces serious financial troubles caused
by corporate failures and bad loans of financial institutions
</P>
<P>
The won stood at 900 against the dollar last September, but it
is now 1,623 against the U.S. currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
