<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for Assistance for Laid-Off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Youth League,
China's leading youth organization, today called on the country's
younger generation to provide voluntary services for urban poor,
most of whom are laid-off from state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The Central Committee of the Youth League issued a circular
listing major categories of voluntary services, including free
legal consultations and household services for poor families, free
vocational training and employment services for laid-off workers,
and persuading business people to supply funding and technology for
reemploying laid-off people.
</P>
<P>
Young people should be urged to donate money and materials to
laid-off workers leading an extremely difficult life, according to
the circular.
</P>
<P>
The circular noted that March 5 will be the 35th anniversary of
Chairman Mao Zedong's call for the country to learn from Lei Feng,
a model soldier of the People's Liberation Army who was always
ready to help others.
</P>
<P>
Lei Feng's name has been widely known to the vast majority of
Chinese citizens since Mao made the call and wrote the special
inscription "Learn From Comrade Lei Feng" on March 5, 1963. March
has been designated as the month in which Chinese citizens
remember Lei Feng by doing something good for the society.
</P>
<P>
"Youth League organizations across the country should focus
on commemorative activities to assist the poor, and should extend
assistance to laid-off workers," according to the circular.
</P>
<P>
Since 1993, the Communist Youth League has consistently
promoted the national campaign "Chinese Young Volunteers in
Action" to immunize the country's youth from the negative
influences of the market economy and prompt them to follow
the example of Lei Feng.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
