<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Anti-drug Campaign Hit by Reinstates of Rebagliati's Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The world-wide anti-drug
campaign was given a heavy blow on Thursday when the Court of
Arbitration for Sport (CAS) overturned the decision of the
International Olympic Committee to strip Canadian snowboarder Ross
Rebagliati of his gold medal.
</P>
<P>
The IOC announced on Wednesday that Rebagliati was disqualified
from the games after a rountine drugs test showed up traces of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
The CAS special tribunal, set up for the first time at the Atlanta
Olympic Summer Games in 1996, consists of independent arbitrators,
chosen for their expertise in arbitration and sports law.
</P>
<P>
In researching their decision, the three arbitrators said:"we do
not suggest for a moment that the use of marijuana should be
condoned, nor do we suggest that sports authorities are not entitled
to exclude athletes found to use cannabis. But if sports
authorities wish to add their own sanctions to those that are
edicted by public authorities, they must do so in an explicit
fashion. That has not been done here.
</P>
<P>
"The Panel recognizes from an ethical and medical perspective,
cannabis consumption is a matter of serious social concern.
</P>
<P>
"CAS is not, however, a criminal court and can neither promulgate
nor apply penal laws. We must decide within the context of the law of
sports, and cannot invent prohibitions or sanctions where none
appear."
</P>
<P>
The chief executive of the Canadian Olympic Association Carol Ann
Letheren said at a press conference that the IOC rules as they stand
have allowed Rebagliati to excape even if the concentration of
marijunana was much higher.
</P>
<P>
"We are simply saying that in this particular occasion there were
no legal grounds for the decision (to strip Rebagliati of his gold
medal).
</P>
<P>
"Clearly the IOC medical code does not have marijuana as a banned
substance. It is labelled as a restricted substance," she said.
</P>
<P>
IOC Director General Francois Carrard said on Wednesday that
metabolized marijuana was detected in an "A" sample, and then a "B"
sample confirmed 17.8 nanograms per milliliter of the substance.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has no minimum amounts set for substance infractions, but
the International Ski Federation to which Rebagliati is a member sets
15 nanogram limit.
</P>
<P>
Deciding between issuing a warning or sanctions to the snowboarder,
both the medical commission and the IOC Executive Board voted in
favour of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The medical commission voted 13-12 to recommend sanctioning the
snowboarder to the IOC which takes the action. The IOC executive
board voted 3-2 with 2 abstentions on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Possession of drugs is illegal in Japan, and Rebagliati had been
questioned by Japanese police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0128 </DOCNO>
