<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Shrimp Farmers Resume Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Shrimp farmers in the
northwest of Sri Lanka are resuming production after a loan of 1
billion rupees (16.1 million U.S. dollars) was offered to revive
the industry.
</P>
<P>
The Central Bank of Sri Lanka has released the loan in a bid to
help the shrimp farmers in the region, who suffered heavy losses
last year due to the spreading of a killer virus, the SEMBV.
</P>
<P>
Local businessmen said Thursday about 35 percent of the
country's 6,000 acres (2,428 hectares) of shrimp farmland in the
northwestern region resumed production at the end of January.
</P>
<P>
Shrimp is an important export item of Sri Lanka. In 1995,
shrimp exports amounted to 47 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Besides the virus, another factor that affected the industry
last year was the continuous rainfall.
</P>
<P>
Excessive rainfall last September and early January reduced the
salinity level of water in the farmland, making it unsuitable to
raise shrimps, the businessmen explained.
</P>
<P>
However, the persistent draught since early January, which is
expected to last till May, has helped improve the salinity level
and enabled farms to begin their production cycles, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
