<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar
weakened Thursday after the release of worse-than-expected jobs
data.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, just 2,400 jobs were created in
January, well below market expectations of 20,000 new jobs, after
the loss of 6,000 positions in December.
</P>
<P>
The number of the unemployed in Australia rose by 3,000 to
756,100, while the jobless rate was 8.2 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar fell nearly half a US cent to close at
67.83 US cents, from 68.28 Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It had begun the day on a weaker note, at 67.78 US cents, after
offshore selling overnight.
</P>
<P>
A slightly weaker Japanese yen against the US dollar and a
softer gold price weighed on the local currency.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar tested lower immediately after the
employment figures were released.
</P>
<P>
Economists said Thursday's data supported the case for no
change in official interest rates.
</P>
<P>
Axiom Funds Management Corp senior economist Matthew Drennan
said the real risk for the Australian economy going forward was
Asia, with the employment outlook turning bearish.
</P>
<P>
Drennan said "the employment outlook is set to sour as the
Asian crisis begins to impact on sectors like tourism and
manufacturing."
</P>
<P>
Hambros fixed income economist Su-Lin Ong said the domestic
market was likely to underperform modestly this year, as growth
remained sound, inflation rose, and the external position
deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 83.63 Japanese yen, down from
84.34 yen Wednesday and at 1.2352 German marks, down from 1.2336
marks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
