<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Master Plan to Control Air Pollution, Acid Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China will unveil a master
plan to combat the country's worsening air pollution and acid
rain, a top environmental official announced today.
</P>
<P>
The program will focus on controlling sulfur dioxide (SO2)
emissions, the main pollutant of the atmosphere and the cause of
acid rain, said Xie Zhenhua, director of the National
Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA) at a news conference here.
</P>
<P>
He said the State Council has approved the NEPA plan that maps
out the sulfur dioxide and acid rain control zones with detailed
measures to fight the environmental threat.
</P>
<P>
According to the plan, all the industrial sources discharging
SO2 must meet national standards before 2000 to ensure the total
amount of sulfur dioxide discharges are brought under control.
</P>
<P>
Areas seriously affected by acid rain should have reversed the
trend by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The annual emission of sulfur dioxide in China is around 23
million tons and 63 cities are suffering from serious SO2
pollution. Some 800,000 square kilometers, or 8.4 percent of the
country's territory, are experiencing acid rain.
</P>
<P>
Xie said China will stem SO2 pollution at its sources. For
example, the country will restrict mining coal with a sulfur
content exceeding 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thermal power plants must install sweetening facilities while a
fee will be charged for sulfur dioxide discharge, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
Measures to improve air quality also include reducing auto
pollution. All vehicles must use lead-free gasoline by 2000 and
existing ones should have installed emission-control devices.
</P>
<P>
"Vehicles without emission-purifying devices, imported or
domestic-made alike, should not be allowed to enter the market in
the future," Xie said.
</P>
<P>
Following the suit of 27 cities -- including Nanjing, Shanghai,
Xiamen and Dalian -- more cities plan to publish on a weekly basis
main indexes of local air quality this year. Beijing is among the
cities which will introduce the report system in the first half of
the year, Xie said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
