</P>
<P>
National turnover was 345.19 million valued at 918.19 million
Australian dollars (624.36 million US dollars), with falls
outnumbering rises 580 to 539.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index closed down 8.2 points at 1,173.5 and
the all industrials index closed up 0.8 at 4,560.0.
</P>
<P>
Major resource companies, BHP, WMC and Rio Tinto, all lost
ground as some investors took profits, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
"Those stocks have had a reasonable good run of late, so it was
just a bit of profit taking," traders said.
</P>
<P>
Topping volume were Telstra installment receipts - up seven
cents on turnover of 14.14 million valued at 49.78 million
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
"I think everyone is comparing Telstra to the Commonwealth Bank
who continued to strip out costs," an institutional stock broker
at Hartley Poynton said.
</P>
<P>
The January job figures, which were below expectations, failed
to provide the equities market with any leads, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
"We were expecting stronger employment data," said a Sydney
broker, "the figures didn't provide any leads."
</P>
<P>
The gold index was down 10.7 points at 1,163.3, with trading in
Sydney gold bullion closed steady at 300.95 US dollars an ounce.
