<HEADLINE> Canadian Press Chief: No Legal Ground to Punish Rebagliati </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Canadian team press chief
Sylie Bigras said on Thursday that there was no legal ground to punish
Canadian snowboarding champion Ross Rebagliati.
</P>
<P>
"IOC codes does not list marijuana as banned substance, it is
listed as restricted substance," she said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The Court of Arbitration for Sport has overturned a decision by the
International Olympic Committee to strip Rebagliati of gold medal.
</P>
<P>
She added the the CAS heard Rebagliati's statement Wednesday
evening. Rebagliati stated that he did not take marijuana since April
1997.
</P>
<P>
The press chief noted that it does not mean Canada was in favour of
taking marijuana. "Just in this case, there is no legal ground to make
any decision to disqualify Rebagliati," she added.
</P>
<P>
IOC Director-General Francois Carrard said on Wednesday that
metabolized marijuana was detected in an "A" sample, and then a "B"
sample confirmed 17.8 nanograms per milliliter of the substance.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has no minimum amounts set for substance infractions, but
the International Ski Federation to which Rebagliati is a member sets
15 nanogram limit.
</P>
<P>
Deciding between issuing a warning or sanctions to the snowboarder,
both the medical commission and the IOC Executive Board voted in
favour of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The medical commission voted 13-12 to recommend sanctioning the
snowboarder to the IOC which takes the action. The IOC executive
board voted 3-2 with 2 abstentions on the matter, Carrard said.
</P>
<P>
Possession of marijuana is illegal in Japan, and Rebagliati was
questioned in a police station in Nagano this afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
