<HEADLINE> Billions Needed to Finance China's Environmental Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China needs at least 450
billion yuan (54 billion dollars) to finance an environmental
protection program expected to be completed by the end of the
century, a high-ranking Chinese environmental official announced
today at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Xie Zhenhua, director of the National Environmental Protection
Agency (NEPA), said that priority will be given to water and air
pollution treatment, controls for sulfur dioxide emissions and
acid rain.
</P>
<P>
All industrial polluting sources across the country are
required to meet discharge standards by year 2000, Xie said, and
protection of the ecological environment should be strengthened in
a practical way.
</P>
<P>
While the central government will coordinate and partly pay for
the regional clean-up efforts, provincial and city governments
will be responsible for their urban areas and regions. Individual
polluters are required to contribute based on the principle that
polluters must pay, Xie said.
</P>
<P>
Financial assistance from the international community,
Sino-foreign cooperation and loans from foreign banks are also
effective channels for fund-raising, he said.
</P>
<P>
Xie had recently announced at a press conference that the
Chinese government would invest 180 billion yuan in environmental
pollution treatment and rebuilding the environment. The investment
will be poured into 1,600 environmental projects, including
pollution treatment in the Huaihe River basin, Taihu Lake area,
and Dianchi Lake, the three most-polluted river basins in the
country.
</P>
<P>
"The environmental pollution is deteriorating across China in
general, with environment in parts of the country improving," said
Xie, when asked to give a general evaluation of China's
environmental situation.
</P>
<P>
"But I have confidence in the Chinese government's drive to
successfully check the environmental pollution by 2000, which will
lead to an overall environmental improvement both in China's
inland areas and the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region," he
emphasized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
