<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arbitrators Reinstate Rebagliati's Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Court of Arbitration for
Sport has overturned the decision of the International Olympic
Committee to strip Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati of his gold
medal after a routine drugs test showed up traces of marijuana.
</P>
<P>
The IOC said it "will comply with all aspects of this award."
</P>
<P>
The CAS sepcial tribunal, set up for the first time at the Atlanta
Olympic Summer Games in 1996, consists of independent arbitrators,
chosen for their expertise in arbitration and sports law.
</P>
<P>
In reaching their decision, the three arbitrators said:"We do not
suggest for a moment that the use of marijuana should be condoned, nor
do we suggest that sports authorities are not entitled to exclude
athletes found to use cannabis.
</P>
<P>
"But if sports authorities wish to add their own sanctions to those
that are edicted by public authorities, they must do so in an explicit
fashion."
</P>
<P>
The panel found that the IOC had not challenged the snowboarder's
claim that he had not taken the drug since April 1997, and that its
presence in his body was due to second-hand ingestion of cannabis
smoke at a going away party.
</P>
<P>
Also among the panel's key findings was the fact that Drug
Formulary Guide issued by the Nagano Olympic Organizing Committee does
not list marijuana as a prohibited substance but as one which should
be used "cautiously". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
