<HEADLINE> Schools in N. Uganda Fail to Operate for Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Many primary and secondary
schools in an Uganda northern district failed to operate in the
new term due to poor sanitation, The New Vision reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
P.J. Ogwang, the district education officer in Lira district,
said Tuesday that only a few schools passed the hygienic check
ordered by Crispus Kiyonga, the Health Minister.
</P>
<P>
The health minister instructed medical authorities late last
month to have checks on hygienic condition of schools before the
new term beginning from earlier this month to guarantee
appropriate conditions for students for prevention from cholera.
</P>
<P>
Ogwang said a joint survey by groups made up of schools,
medical personnel and the cholera task force have found many
schools lack of latrines, urinals and running water.
</P>
<P>
A directive had been issued as a result of the joint survey to
delay the operation of the schools under hygienic standard for
two or three weeks during which the schools can improve their
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Cholera hit 26 of total 45 districts of the country and has
killed more than 400 people in recent rainy months.  
</P>
