<HEADLINE> China to Tackle Major Public Security Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China this year will continue
taking severe actions to crack down on crimes directly harming
public security, said an official with the Central Committee for
Comprehensive Management of Public Security (CCCMPS).
</P>
<P>
According to the official, public security work inside and
outside big- and medium-size state-owned enterprises will be
further enhanced to create a better social environment for the
enterprises' production activities.
</P>
<P>
Crimes concerning damage to telecommunications facilities,
railways, civil aviation facilities, electric power facilities,
oil fields and mines will be strictly punished, the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that public security work in areas around middle and
primary schools will receive more attention this year, and legal
education for students will be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
Also, he said, efforts will be undertaken this year to better
guide the transient population and manage the work well.
</P>
<P>
"Various training programs to improve young laborers' legal
awareness, morality and job skills will be organized," the
official said, "and the house-renting business will be rectified
to prevent law-violation cases from happening as well as to
protect the lawful rights of the floating population."
</P>
<P>
Another major issue China will focus on this year is to help
those just released from prison, the official said.
</P>
<P>
CCCMPS, a regular organization of the Chinese Communist Party's
Central Committee founded in 1991, was supposed to provide
assistance to China's leadership on public security issues.
</P>
