<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Says Acid Rain Has Two-way Effect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The director of China's
Environmental Protection Agency, Xie Zhenhua, says that China has
been hit by acid rain for the past 10 years, but whether the
effect is felt in neighbouring countries remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
The problem of acid rain is becoming more serious, Xie told a
press conference here today, and China has begun research with
Japan and the Republic of Korea and they plan to take steps to
solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
He acknowledged that acid rain affects about 30 percent of
China's area, and that parts of 14 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions, where the situation is most serious, have been
defined as acid rain control zones and will be the focus of the
efforts over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
These zones cover 800,000 square kilometers, or 8.4 percent of
the country's total land area.  
</P>
