<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Stock Exchange to Implement News Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Stock Exchange
(PSE) is set to implement new rules and regulations governing
securities borrowing and lending (SBL) and short selling of
securities in the country starting the third quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed Thursday by the Product Development
Department of the PSE which was tasked to come out with these
rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Product Development analyst Violeta Defeo said the draft of the
new rules and regulations is now being studied and reviewed by
PSE's Board of Governors for its final approval.
</P>
<P>
Although she declined to say what these rules and regulations
are all about, she made sure that these rules are "beneficial" to
the interests of the capital market in the country.
</P>
<P>
A SBL transaction involves the loan of securities by a lender
who owns or controls them, to a borrower who needs them to support
trading strategies or settlement of obligations.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of SBL and short selling would help the
country establish a system of borrowing and lending to protect the
interests of all stake holders.
</P>
<P>
The reason of introducing SBL and short selling in the country
is for them to be institutionalized onshore since the common
practice is for investors to borrow securities from overseas,
particularly Hong Kong, where this scheme is being practiced right
now, says Defeo.
</P>
<P>
In a PSE study, the only countries in Asia and the Pacific that
have yet to adopt the practice of SBL and short selling onshore
are the Philippines and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"One of the major reasons for the non-existence of SBL in the
Philippines has been the lack of regulations that would provide
clear and specific guidelines for both local and international
market players," the study noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
