<HEADLINE> Anti-drug Campaign Hit by Reinstates of Rebagliati's Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The world-wide anti-drug
campaign was given a heavy blow on Thursday when the Court of
Arbitration for Sport overturned the decision of the International
Olympic Committee to strip Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati of his
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
The IOC announced on Wednesday that Rebagliati was disqualified
from the games after a rountine drugs test showed up traces of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
IOC Director General Francois Carrard said on Wednesday that
metabolized marijuana was detected in an "A" sample, and then a "B"
sample confirmed 17.8 nanograms per milliliter of the substance.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has no minimum amounts set for substance infractions, but
the International Ski Federation to which Rebagliati is a member sets
15 nanogram limit.
</P>
<P>
Deciding between issuing a warning or sanctions to the snowboarder,
both the medical commission and the IOC Executive Board voted in
favour of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The medical commission voted 13-12 to recommend sanctioning the
snowboarder to the IOC which takes the action. The IOC executive
board voted 3-2 with 2 abstentions on the matter.
</P>
<P>
Possession of drugs is illegal in Japan, and Rebagliati had been
questioned by Japanese police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
