<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Share prices reversed its
upward trend and declined on the Singapore market on Thursday as
the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index (STII) lost 20.96
points to close at 1,600.29 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers noted that share prices dropped by 1.3 percent as
investors locked in profits and took a rest from six straight days
of gains.
</P>
<P>
They also said that weaker regional currencies contributed to
the stock market sell-off. Share prices had risen after Indonesia
announced that it planned to set up a currency board system.
However, the dealers said that the situation is still uncertain
and investors continued to seek trading opportunities amid
volatility.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume shrank to 697.47 million units, valued
at 697.66 million Singapore dollars (about 425.4 million US
dollars). Declines overwhelmed advances by 380 to 34, while 198
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 60.72 million units. It was followed by
Rekapac which had 55.38 million shares traded. MBf Capital was
next with 27.98 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign led the gainers of
the day as it rose by 1.4 dollars to finish at 24.9 Singapore
dollars. Asean Fund increased by 75 cents to end at 9.25 Singapore
dollars. SPH was up by 60 cents to close at 20.2 Singapore
dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Bukit Sambawang was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.15 dollars to end at 9.65 Singapore dollars. Malaya
Banking 200 fell by 1.05 dollars to close at 5.55 Singapore
dollars. DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Foreign and Malaya
Banking lost 60 cents each to finish at 13.7 and 5.6 Singapore
dollars respectively.  
</P>
