<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa's Public Service Reform Needs Improvement: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- African countries have
had mixed success in reforming inefficient and corruption-prone
bureaucracies over the past decade, a report of the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) said.
</P>
<P>
There has been some progress in down-sizing and cost-cutting,
but decidedly less in improving the quality of public services,
Thursday's Business Day paper quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The working paper by the IMF fiscal affairs department
emphasizes the need for improved "recruitment, remuneration and
promotion policies, based on performance rather than
connections".
</P>
<P>
The paper looked at 32 countries, including Kenya, Ghana, Cote
d'Ivoire, Uganda, Zambia, South Africa and Zimbabwe. Twenty-nine
of the countries undertook public sector reforms as part of IMF
structural adjustment packages starting in the mid-eighties.
</P>
<P>
Overall, the governments have shed employees since the
beginning of the decade. The 24 central governments for which
there was adequate data shrank their total payroll from 2 million
U.S. dollars in 1991 to 1.8 million U.S. dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, state wage bills fell from an average of
7.2 percent to 5.8 percent of gross domestic product (GDP) in the
32 countries, and they accounted for a reduced share of
government expenditure.
</P>
<P>
Real wages per public servant fell an average 12 percent in 20
countries.
</P>
<P>
However, most of this positive trend was mainly due to the
devaluation of the central African franc in 1994, which slashed
real wages in much of Francophone Africa, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The falling real public service wages also meant that few
countries were able to narrow salary differentials with
non-governmental sectors -- an important objective if governments
are to attract and retain skilled and honest personnel, it said.
</P>
<P>
The desirable widening of salary gap between bottom and
top-level employees has been slow, and some countries, such as
Cameroon, has reduced the highest public servant salary in
relation to the lowest.
</P>
<P>
The report said this could threaten public bureaucracies'
ability to keep talent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Not Favoring Use of Force to Resolve Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry
spokesman Zhu Bangzao today reiterated that China does not favor
the use of force to resolve the arms inspection crisis in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Zhu told a regular news conference that U.S. Ambassador to the
United Nations Bill Richardson will, as a special envoy of U.S.
President Bill Clinton, come to China to exchange views on the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
China will expound its views to the United States and its
proposal to seek a peaceful solution of the crisis, he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the crisis, China, as a permanent member
of the United Nations Security Council, has called on all parties
concerned to exercise a sober and restrained attitude and proposed
a settlement of the issue through dialogue and cooperation to
avoid escalating the crisis into armed conflict, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has closely consulted and cooperated with
all concerned parties and made constructive efforts to seek a
proper settlement of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Although the crisis is escalating, China supports political and
diplomatic efforts and will continue to play a positive role to
seek a peaceful solution of the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stated China's stance remains unchanged, that it
opposes the use of force to resolve the crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese hope that concerned parties will take a flexible
and restrained attitude to settle the crisis, the spokesman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
