<HEADLINE> HK to Be Well Positioned for Information Age: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong needs to have
itself well prepared for the upcoming Information Age in the 21st
century, a top official of the Special Administrative Region (SAR)
government said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the first Hong Kong Information
Infrastructure Exposition and Conference, the SAR's Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa said: "Information technology will shape
the 21st century ...we must ensure that Hong Kong is well placed
to reap the benefits of this move."
</P>
<P>
"We cannot underestimate the challenges and opportunities
afforded us by the Information Age. They will be as momentous in
their way as the Industrial Revolution some one hundred or so
years ago," said Tung.
</P>
<P>
Information technology will enhance Hong Kong's
competitiveness, sustain its economic growth, improve services,
upgrade quality of life, said Tung. But he stressed: "It is now
enough for the experts to be prepared for the Information Age. We,
Hong Kong as a whole, must be ready for its coming and ready to
master it. We must master information technology or else it will
become our master."
</P>
<P>
Tung has taken it as one of his administration's key tasks to
push forward the development of information infrastructure in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
In his first Policy Address in October 1997, Tung announced
that one bureau secretary would coordinate the SAR government work
in information technology, broadcasting and telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government announced Wednesday that the restructured
Information Technology and Broadcasting Bureau would undertake the
important task to help lead Hong Kong into the Information Age.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the SAR government would allocate 2.5 billion HK
dollars (320 million US dollars) to provide information technology
facilities for schools and for training of teachers.
</P>
<P>
Recently, the government has reached an agreement with Hong
Kong Telecom to put an end to the company's monopoly on Hong
Kong's international telephone services, a move to encourage
further competition on telecommunications market.
</P>
<P>
But Tung said Thursday: "This is just a taste of what is
happening now, a mere foreshadowing of things to come."
</P>
<P>
The four-day Information Infrastructure Exposition and
Conference, the first of its kind ever held in Hong Kong, is aimed
to promote the public understanding of the information technology
and its impact on people's lives.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
