<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Eyes Information Society </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Just clicking the mouse, a
tourist can see on a computer screen the virtual street in Hong
Kong he has exhausted himself to comb a map for but failed.
</P>
<P>
The program, dubbed electronic street guide, simply shows how
information technology changes people's way of work and life. Yet
it is only a tiny part in the future society being displayed at
the first Hong Kong Information Infrastructure Exposition and
Conference, which was opened here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At the "Future Society" pavilion, ten simulated models of
future home, office, street, government services, mobility,
financial services, electronic world, transportation, community
information, and information entertainment are presented, putting
visitors into a fascinating and entertaining world of information
technology.
</P>
<P>
As part of the Information Infrastructure Exposition and
Conference, the futuristic pavilion is aimed to promote the public
understanding of the fast pace of information technology and its
far-reaching impact on their daily lives.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR)'s Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa Thursday officiated the opening ceremony
of the Exposition, saying that information technology shapes the
21st century, adds Hong Kong's competitiveness, sustains Hong
Kong's economic growth, and enriches entertainment in leisure
time.
</P>
<P>
The four-day Exposition and Conference, the first of its kind
in Hong Kong focusing on the development of information
infrastructure, was jointly organized by the Trade Development
Council (TDC) and the Office of Telecommunications Authority
(OFTA),
</P>
<P>
A high-level conference was held on the first two days of the
Exposition for both local and overseas experts to exchange their
views on the development of information technology and
infrastructure. Meanwhile, a commercial exhibition showed a wide
spectrum of advanced information technology and telecommunications
services and products from 70 companies.  
</P>
