<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks Investment for Mineral Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has encouraged businessmen from both at home and
abroad to invest in the development of mineral resources in the
country, The Guardian said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day dialogue for chief executives of mining
companies in north Tanzania's Arusha Wednesday, Mkapa said
Tanzania boasts both abundant natural resources and social
stability.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania is rich in gold, diamonds, rubies and other
gemstones, as well as nickel, copper, cobalt and other mineral
resources, Mkapa told more than 300 chief executives from local
and foreign mining companies.
</P>
<P>
The east African country also takes pride in peace, political
stability and social harmony and concord since independence in
1961, he said.
</P>
<P>
The creation of a sound macro-economic management system is
also an important factor, the paper quoted president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Other favorable factors include an internationally
competitive, predictable and legal and fiscal framework, good
governance as well as the government's persistent fight against
corruption.
</P>
<P>
The government has grown aware of dealing with problems in
infrastructure facilities, education, the president said.
</P>
<P>
The government will remove all bottlenecks for investors to
operate smoothly in the mining sector, the president assured.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve Tanzania's global competitiveness in
trade, the president said, the government has repealed the
restrictive National Investment (Promotion and Protection) Act of
1990, replacing it with the Tanzanian Investment Act of 1997 last
October.
</P>
<P>
The government approved, in its October 1997 session, a new
special fiscal package for the mining sector as a further
testimony to the country's commitment to encourage private
investment in that sector, he said.
</P>
<P>
Clauses of the new package include full exemption on sales tax
and import and export and excise duties on equipment directly
related to mineral exploration, development and production,
according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government is paying greater attention to the
development of minerals. According to official sources,
Tanzania's mineral sector is currently contributing 1.4 percent
of the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) up from a mere 0.5 percent in
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is sponsored by the World Bank in collaboration
with local financial institutions, mining companies and the IPP
Group of Companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
