<HEADLINE> 50 Most Competitive Cities Serve as Economic, Social Powerhouses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The 50 most competitive cities
in China account for 27.1 percent of the country's Gross Domestic
Product, and serve as the locomotive for social development,
according to the State Statistical Bureau (SSB).
</P>
<P>
The conclusion was drawan after a survey on 219 Chinese cities
at or above prefecture-level.
</P>
<P>
The SSB graded the 50 cities into two tiers in terms of their
economic force and social development.
</P>
<P>
The first tier incorporates 19 cities, namely Shanghai,
Beijing, Guangzhou, Tianjin, Shenyang, Wuhan, Nanjing, Dalian,
Shenzhen, Hangzhou, Harbin, Chengdu, Chongqing, Xi'an,
Shijiazhuang, Changchun, Qingdao, Jinan and Changsha.
</P>
<P>
In the second tier of 31 cities are some capitals of big inland
provinces and three special economic zones -- Xiamen, Shantou and
Zhuhai.
</P>
<P>
The SSB said the indexes for the development of economy,
education, science and technology in the 50 cities are far higher
than the average of China's urban areas and they have become
China's high-tech industrial bases.  
</P>
