<HEADLINE> Japan, Poland Agree on Visa Abolition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Poland agreed Thursday
to abolish visas for the two countries' nationals visiting each
other's countries in a bid to promote bilateral exchanges, Kyodo
News Service reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a meeting between Japanese
Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and visiting Polish President
Aleksander Kwasniewski.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which is expected to be put into force in
April, travelers and businessmen of the two countries will be
allowed to stay in each other's countries for as long as three
months if they do not intend to engage in work, said government
officials.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also reached an accord on holding a vice
foreign ministerial talks in Warsaw in the middle of the next
month with focus on global political issues such as illegal
narcotic trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Kwasniewski, who attended the opening ceremony of the ongoing
Nagano Winter Olympic Games Saturday, also sought substantial
increase in Japan's private-sector investment in Poland, the
officials said. 
</P>
