<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Congress Committee Probes Air Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A House of Representative
committee has begun its investigation of the February 2 crash of
Cebu Pacific Flight 387 in which 104 people were killed, local
press reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the committee found a route deviation by the
plane was a major factor leading to the worst air disaster, but so
far no body has claimed responsibility for the approval of the
detour.
</P>
<P>
The ill-fated plane made a stopover in Tacloban city en its
route from Manila to Cagayan de Oro city in the south. But the
detour forced it to fly an abandoned route which includes several
high mountain peaks blanketed by thick clouds.
</P>
<P>
Testifying at Wednesday's hearing, Air Transportation Office
chief Carlos Tanega blamed the Civil Aeronautics Board (CAB) for
allowing the illegal stopover, saying his office was not informed
of the flight diversion.
</P>
<P>
"We are not aware that plane was a diverted flight...We thought
it was regular flight to Tacloban," Tanega said.
</P>
<P>
However, Tanega's testimony contradicted Transportation
Secretary Josefina Lichauco's early statement, saying Tanega had
admitted to her the ATO approved the altered route to Tacloban.
</P>
<P>
"It was one of the first things I asked Tanega and he answered
in the affirmative, and the next question therefore is whether the
passengers had been informed about such a deviation to Tacloban
and here, my preliminary information is that they were not," she
said.
</P>
<P>
CAB flight operation chief Leticia Dumlao justified the
diversion as a technical landing, but she failed to explain why
she allowed the detour which violated the Contract of Carriage
between the passengers and the airline.
</P>
<P>
The Cebu Pacific management asserted that the plane secured the
ATO approval for its flight plan and the technical stopover was
announced to the passengers before the plane took off.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, rescue operations were still undergoing at the crash
site, but at a very slow speed because of bad weather. Rescuers
had retrieved 92 bags filled with body parts of the victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
