<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF: Manila Least Affected in Asian Currency Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) Thursday reiterated that the Philippines was the least
affected amid the Asian currency crisis due to solid progress made
by the government.
</P>
<P>
An IMF report reaching here said that despite the peso
devaluation and soaring interest rates, the Philippines' fourth
quarter gross domestic product grew 4.7 percent, taking the
full-year figure to 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
"That comfortably exceeded the IMF's forecast of 4.4 percent in
1997, representing the fourth consecutive year of high growth,"
the report said.
</P>
<P>
It added that because the country did not experience the decade
of high growth rates enjoyed by some of its neighbors, "the
financial sector excesses are not as pronounced, and in
particular, banks' exposure to the property sector has been
correspondingly low."
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the Philippine government succeeded
in introducing a raft of deregulation, privatization and
comprehensive tax reforms to ensure dependable revenues under the
IMF's tutelage.
</P>
<P>
The multi-national institution that whoever is the successor of
President Fidel Ramos in June this year will inherit an economy
less buffeted by the Asian currency crisis than its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
At present, an IMF mission is in the country to review the
economy and discuss with the government its graduation from the
IMF's 35 years of supervision by March this year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also said that the Philippines will soon open talks
with the fund for a new facility of about 2.7 billion U.S.
dollars. The facility is a pre-cautious arrangement and would be
withdrawn when the country's financial situation suddenly worsens.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
