<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Debt to Rise Sharply in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
projected that its debt this year will rise by 35.7 percent to
170. 4 billion pesos (4 billion U.S. dollars) due to the currency
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Business World Thursday reported that the
forecast was based on the assumption that the average exchange
rate for 1998 will be 42 pesos per dollar.
</P>
<P>
The higher debt burden will come amid expected pressures from
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) for the state to produce a
hefty fiscal surplus by yearend.
</P>
<P>
The report said the projected debt figure had been presented to
an IMF mission who was here to decide the country's possible exit
by March from 35 years of IMF tutelage.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the country's debt burden was estimated at 125.6
billion pesos.
</P>
<P>
Of the planned total debt burden for 1998, some 63 percent will
be domestic debt and the rest foreign debt. This means that the
country would rely more on domestic borrowings by selling
government securities to meet its fiscal surplus target.
</P>
<P>
National treasurer Caridad Valdehuesa said the increase in the
debt would impact on the national government's ability to achieve
a fiscal surplus this year.
</P>
<P>
"If domestic revenues exceed domestic and foreign debt, well
and good, but if there is a shortfall, the first line of defense
should be to cut down on expenditures," she said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government ended up with a one-billion-peso
budget surplus from an earlier-projected 16 billion due to
depressed revenues from import-related taxes and higher interest
payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
