<HEADLINE> Shanghai to Control High-Grade Open-Market Housing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's financial
and industrial center, will strictly control construction of
high-grade, open-market housing in next three years, according to
Mayor Xu Kuangdi.
</P>
<P>
Xu emphasized today that, at the same time, Shanghai will build
houses at fairly low prices to meet the needs of families with
different incomes.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years Shanghai completed 57 million square
meters of new houses for a per-capita average of nine square
meters of living space for each resident.
</P>
<P>
Xu said during the on-going first session of the Shanghai
Municipal People's Congress that Shanghai will accelerate the
reconstruction of old residential quarters, dismantle 3.65 million
square meters of rundown houses, and build a series of residential
quarters between the ring areas.
</P>
<P>
By the year 2000, every resident will possess 10 square meters
of living space, he noted. Concerning questions on housing reform,
Xu said efforts will be made to invigorate the real estate market
and regulate real estate management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
