<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain: Use of Force Against Iraq Not Decided </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Minister of State at the British
Foreign Office Derek Fatchett has said that no decision on the use
of force against Iraq has been taken yet.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egyptian Al Ahram newspaper published on
Thursday, the British official said that the military action,
however, "could not be excluded" if Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
refused to yield to the will of the world.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett will arrive here Thursday for a brief visit to Egypt
within the context of a tour of the area that has so far taken him
to Oman and the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
His talks during the tour cover Iraq's crisis with the United
Nations and the British efforts that aimed at reaching a
diplomatic solution to the crisis, he told the Arabic daily.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Britain have been preparing for a
military strike against Iraq over its denial of full access of the
United Nations arms inspectors to the sites suspected of hiding
lethal weapons.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohamed Saeed Al-Sahhaf said here
Wednesday that Iraqi decided to open eight presidential sites,
which he said mean all monitoring sites, to international arms
experts appointed by the U.N. secretary general.
</P>
<P>
Britain has rejected the plan and expressed its solidarity with
the U.S. in case Washington makes true on its threat of military
punishment over Baghdad's alleged failure to comply with the
U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Britain supports the diplomatic initiatives of Russia and the
Arab League to solve the crisis. But we should be ready for
military action if diplomacy failed to help the U.N. inspectors
return to Iraq and carry out their mission," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has to comply with all the U.N. resolutions that stipulate
the U.N. inspectors be allowed to complete their mission, he
said. Otherwise a tough stand should be adopted towards Baghdad's
intransigence, he added.
</P>
<P>
Later in the day, Fatchett will hand over a message to Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak from British Prime Minister Tony
Blair. The British diplomat will also meet with Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa and the Arab League chief Esmat Abdel Meguid on the
regional issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
