<HEADLINE> Using Force Against Iraq Leads to Dire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt has reiterated that
resorting to force in resolving the current U.N.-Iraq standoff
will lead to dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Presidential Political Advisor Osama Al Baz,
addressing a youth gathering organized Wednesday night, stressed
that Egypt is in favor of a political solution to this crisis, the
Middle East News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He strongly blasted the U.S. hardline policy towards Iraq and
said Egypt is working together with Iraq and "other active
countries" such as Russia, France and China in quest of a peaceful
solution to the Iraqi crisis that preserves Iraq's dignity.
</P>
<P>
Baz urged on both Iraq and the United Nations to seek a
political solution to this crisis, warning that resorting to force
will lead to dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Egyptian cabinet has decided to set up a
five-member committee to draw up a plan in case that the
threatened U.S. military action against Iraq materialize.
</P>
<P>
"This aims to protect the Egyptian expatriates (in Iraq)
against any negative likelihoods," Information Minister Safwat
el-Sheif said after the Cabinet Wednesday held lengthy discussions
on the Iraqi crisis.
</P>
<P>
The committee will be composed of ministers of the interior,
transport, social affairs and manpower and the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak warned that
there appears no relaxation of a military threat against Iraq as
the U.S. is augmenting its military presence in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
"What I fear is Iraq coming under a strike for failure to
implement the U.N. resolutions. and no one would then be able to
prevent the U.S. from mounting such a blow," Mubarak told
reporters on the possibility of a military option.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have been preparing for a military strike
against Iraq over its rejection of full access to the U.N. arms
inspection team to its presidential sites suspected of hiding
lethal weapons, and its demand for reorganization of the
U.N. special commission on scrapping Iraqi weapons of mass
destruction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
