<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Norwegians Set Records in Winter Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian skiier and skater
Bjoern Daehlie and Aadne Sondral set records on the sixth day of the
18th Olympic Winter Games with victories in the men's 10km cross country
skiing classical race and the men's 1,500m speed skating on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the day's first medal event, Daehlie held off bad weather and
other medal contenders to cross the finish line with a winning time of
27 minutes and 24.5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Daehlie became the first male athlete to win six
Winter Olympic golds and the second to have such achievement. Lidia
Skoblikova, women skater from former Soviet Union, collected a total
of six golds in 1960 and 1964 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
Markus Gandler of Austria was second with eight seconds behind and
Italian Mika Myllylae, gold medal winner in Monday's 30km classical
race, was third with further 15.6 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
National hero Daehlie, who finished a disappointing 20th in the
men's 30km, led at every split of the race and collapsed in exhaustion
at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie had trained hard in his career. In his 1997 autobiography,
he estimated that he covered 150,000 kilometers on skis, foot or
cycling over the previous decade --the equivalent of alomost four
trips round the world.
</P>
<P>
Philip Boit, the only athlete representing Kenya which makes its
debut at Winter Olympics, finished 50th in 47 minutes and 25.5
seconds, a time that Daehlie Bjoern could finish the distance two
times.
</P>
<P>
While in the ice rink of M-Wave, Sondral smashed the world record
of the 1,500m speed skating as well as Dutch's hope of the title.
</P>
<P>
Sondral, armed with flap skates, was timed one minute and 47.87
seconds to win the race, beating three Dutch rivals to the lower
placings.
</P>
<P>
Ids Postmas was second at 1:48.13 and another Dutch skater Rintje
Ritsma, who set the world mark of 1:48.88 last December, finished
third at 1:48.52.
</P>
<P>
Braving steady rain in mountains, Larissa Lazutina of Russia won
the women's 10km cross country skiing free pursuit at 46 minutes and
6.9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The Russian skiier spent three Olympics and six years to win her
first Olympic gold medal, but it took her only five days to win her
second one.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 5km cross country skiing classical race on Monday,
she held off strong Norwegian rivals and heavy snow to win the title.
</P>
<P>
With the win in the pursuit, she became the only ahthlete who has
collected two gold medals at the current games.
</P>
<P>
The men's and women's snowboarding halfpipe event were taken by
Swiss and German boarders. Gian Simmen scored 85.2 points to win the
men's event for Switzerland and Nicola Thost came first at 74.6 points
in the women's discipline.
</P>
<P>
Bad Weather continued to have its say in competiton, forcing the
cancellation of two Alpine events, the men's downhill and combined
downhill. The two events were re-scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati was questioned by Japanese
police on Thursday. Rebagliati was disqualified and stripped of men's
giant slalom gold medal by the International Olympic Committee after
being tested positive for marijuana.
</P>
<P>
The IOC said this morning that it was will to cooperate with
investigation by Japanese police of the case. "I can see no reason
why the IOC wouldn't cooperate with the local authorities," Michele
Verdier, IOC's spokesperson said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian delegation has appealing to the case, and the Sports
Arbitration Penal will make a decision within today.
</P>
<P>
After six day competitions, Germany roared to the top of the medal
standings with four golds, four silvers and four bronzes. Russia was
second at four golds and three silvers. Winter sports powerhouse
Norway was third at three golds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
