<HEADLINE> Turkish PM Leaves for Ukraine on Official Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Mesut
Yilmaz left here Thursday morning for a two-day official visit to
Ukraine to boost political and economic ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before his departure for Ukraine at Ankara Esenboga
Airport, Yilmaz said that the development of bilateral ties
between Ukraine and Turkey would make contributions to peace and
stability in this region.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz is the first Turkish prime minister to visit Ukraine
since it gained independence from the former Soviet Union in
1991.
</P>
<P>
"We attache great importance to Ukraine's independence,
sovereignty and territorial integrity protection and economic
reform process," said Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is one of the first countries to recognize Ukraine's
independence in 1991.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Yilmaz will meet Ukrainian President Leonid
Kuchma, Prime Minister Valeriy Pustovoytenko, Chairman of Supreme
Soviet (Parliament Speaker) Alexandr Moroz and other high-ranking
officials, as well as representatives of leading economic
organizations.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between the two countries exceeded one
billion U.S. dollars in 1995 and 1996. Turkish contractors have
undertaken projects in Ukraine worth nearly 300 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
