<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sondral Sets World Record, Wins 1,000 Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian Aadne Sondral beat
his strong Dutch rivals won the men's 1,000-meter speed skating gold
medal and set a new world record Thursday at the Nagano Winter Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
Sondral skated one minute 47.78 for his first Olympic gold, edging
Dutchman Rintje Ritsma, who set the previous world mark of 1:48.88
last December in the Netherlands, to third with 1:48.52.
</P>
<P>
The Sondral's new world record was second created at the current
Olympic speed Skating at the "M-Wave" rink, where the first world
record was created since new slap skates had been used.
</P>
<P>
Gianni Romme, also from the Netherlands, rewrote the first world
speed skating record of the men's 5,000 meters last Sunday at the
Olympics, which opened last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ritsma's countryman Ids Postma, who ranked second at World Cup,
just behind Ritsma, took the silver by clocking 1:48.13.
</P>
<P>
All three broke the old mark, but sondral was the best and the
surprise winner although he said he was going to win the race before
the Games.
</P>
<P>
The 26-year-old, fourth finisher for the event in Lillehammer in
1994 when the speed skating was dominated by Norwegian superstar
Johann Olav Koss, skated in inner lane against Postma in the last
second of 23 pairs and looked to break the record after he finished
1,000 meters in 1:19.08, the best and same time with his strong
contender Postma at the stage.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian, however, pulled away with a spectacular dash and was
time of only 27.92 seconds, compared with Postma's 28.12 seconds, in
last 500 meters to seal the victory.
</P>
<P>
"I said I am going to win the gold, and now I did. I am so happy,"
said the father of a one year old child. "I want to send it (gold
medal) to my mother."
</P>
<P>
"It was the best race I've ever done. For me, it's very important
to have enough speed in the first 300 meters. I concentrated really
hard on that. That's why I used both my arms in the first turn. Ids is
normally a good opener, so I knew if I stayed close to him, I would be
OK."
</P>
<P>
Sondral injured in October, 1996, during training in Inzell, and
was not back in full shape until January, 1997. But he skated a good
season and ranks third now at World Cup.
</P>
<P>
Postma was a bit disappointed with his silver, saying "I thought I
could have won the gold, but in the last curve, I had some problems. I
had a good race, but Aadne was faster. It was a very fast race."
</P>
<P>
The much more disappointed was Ritsma, the world champion and first
place in the World Cup rankings.
</P>
<P>
Known variously as "Tarzan, Alollo and Superman" by his adoring
fans, Ritsma skated against Kevin Overland of Canada at outer lane in
the last pair and had slower start with 24.36 seconds, compared with
Postsma's 23.85 and Sondral's 24.00. He came back to surpassed over
Overland but not enough to reach his gold medal goal.
</P>
<P>
Overland placed only 20th with a slow time of 1:52.07. Another
Dutchman Jan Bos was fourth in 1:49.75, one of three skaters breaking
the 1:50 barrier for Thursday's race.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
