<HEADLINE> U.S. May Suspend Mediation Efforts: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States may
suspend mediating the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, if the two
sides refuse to accept its proposal on Israeli redeployment in
the West Bank, a newspaper report disclosed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a front-page story, local newspaper The Jerusalem Post
reported that Washington may take the step if the current talks
held between U.S. officials and Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators in Washington fail to achieve a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh and Palestinian
negotiator Saeb Erekat are currently in Washington to conduct
talks with U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Middle East peace envoy Dennis Ross met Wednesday with the
two sides, which agreed to continue negotiations in the region
next week under the supervision of U.S. Ambassador to Israel
Edward Walker.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Israeli officials as saying that the U.S. is
trying to press Israel and the Palestinian side to accept its
"bridging proposal" on a double-digit redeployment in the West
Bank within three months.
</P>
<P>
The proposal demands Israel transfer 13 percent of Area C
under total Israeli control to Area A under total Palestinian
control; of this, 2 percent should be transferred to the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) immediately, and the rest
would be transferred over 90 days according to the PNA's
fulfillment of its obligations.
</P>
<P>
Besides the above-mentioned redeployment, there will be an
additional Israeli redeployment from sections of Area B, where
Israel retains security control but is under PNA civilian
authority.
</P>
<P>
The report said U.S. officials had confirmed that if the two
sides' positions remain too far apart, Washington may call a
time-out on its mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
The report added that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu fears that if the peace talks break down, the U.S. will
not only cease its mediation efforts, but also will begin
re-evaluating its entire position on the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Erekat said in Washington Wednesday that the Palestinian side
had rejected a U.S. proposal for an Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank and called the suggested percentages "unrealistic."
</P>
<P>
Marwan Kanafani, PNA President Yasser Arafat's spokesman who
also attended the Washington talks, complained about the
reluctance of the U.S. and international community to increase
pressure on Israel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PNA deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) said
Wednesday that the PNA would continue to demand full
implementation of the Oslo peace accords.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Moscow at the end of his Russian visit, Abbas
called on Russia to increase involvement in the peace process in
order to achieve a just compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0189 </DOCNO>
