<HEADLINE> Israeli Teachers' Strike for Compensation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli parents started
Thursday to keep their children home from secondary schools for
two days to protest the Education Ministry's refusal to meet the
teachers' demands of compensation for after-school activities.
</P>
<P>
The Israel Parents Association (IPA) made the decision
following Wednesday's failure of conciliation between the
Secondary School Teachers Association (SSTA) and their employers.
</P>
<P>
Supported by secondary school teachers, the SSTA has for
several months requested the Education Ministry to pay extra money
for teachers who organize after-school activities and no
agreement has been reached till now by the two sides.
</P>
<P>
SSTA had organized several strikes during the past few months
aimed at forcing the Education Ministry to meet the teachers'
demands. Such strikes affected badly the education of students.
</P>
<P>
Efforts continued on Wednesday to get representatives of the
SSTA and their employers back to the negotiating table as the IPA
announced to keep school children home from Thursday, but the two
sides failed again to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
National Labor Court on Wednesday also refused a request by
the Union of Local Authority and the Education Ministry to order
the teachers to cancel the sanctions, asking the sides to give
the conciliation process another two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the ministry's treatment towards teachers, IPA said
on Wednesday that its strike will be renewed next week if the
ministry still refuses to match the teachers' demands.
</P>
<P>
The Histadrut (national trade union) Teachers Union (HTU) also
organized several strikes in the past to support the SSTA. If it
organizes another strike for the same purpose, the entire
education system in Israel would b paralyzed again.
</P>
<P>
The Education Ministry blasted the IPA for calling this two-day
strike, saying the parents had no legal standing to take such
action, and called the teachers to return to conciliation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Eyes Markets Beyond Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Asia is not the entire
focus of Boeing, which is eyeing Europe and other markets for its
jets, an official of the Seattle manufacturer said recently.
</P>
<P>
Tim Meskill, Boeing's market outlook manager, said that the
company has many options in the face of delayed orders from Asian
airlines.
</P>
<P>
Europe, where air traffic increased a surprising 10 percent
last year, seems to be Boeing's first market alternative.
</P>
<P>
Boeing expects the total number of its planes order in 1998 to
be near the 502 booked last year. Most will have to come from
outside Asia, earlier seen as the leading market.
</P>
<P>
European demand will come not only from established national
carriers but also from the smaller regional carriers emerging
through more liberal laws enacted by the European Community.
</P>
<P>
Charter operators that carry about half the passenger traffic
within Europe are also growing, Meskill said.
</P>
<P>
European airliners accounted for 63 percent of Boeing's
announced orders in 1997, although Europe is rival Airbus
industries' home territory.
</P>
<P>
Scandinavian Airline System and British Airways are among
Boeing's important customers, he added.
</P>
<P>
Aviation analysts say that Boeing's production problems and
delivery delays have given Airbus an advantage in European
orders.
</P>
<P>
The four-nation consortium also has the backing of French,
German, British and Spanish governments. Startup European airlines
could be pressed to choose the European manufacturer, which is
especially aggressive in pricing.
</P>
<P>
However, the analysts still expect Boeing to keep an upper
hand in the widebody race.
</P>
<P>
European charter operators are also expected to provide more
orders for Boeing.
</P>
<P>
Outside Europe, Meskill said, Central and South America offer
sales opportunities. Airlines there are growing steadily, but
mostly in regional service that require smaller jets.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the smaller states of the former Soviet Union could
also be a market in the long run, say the analysts, citing that
Russian air industry is not likely to expand rapidly to compete
with Boeing and Airbus.
</P>
<P>
An Russian airline will take delivery of its first Boeing 777
in April.
</P>
<P>
Meskill said that Boeing still does not know when the Asian
financial crisis will end and how long the delivery delays by
Asian airlines will last. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0192 </DOCNO>
