<HEADLINE> Overseas Tourism Hits New High in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China had a record 57.59
million overseas tourists in 1997, a rise of 12.6 percent over the
previous year. Overseas tourists include visitors from Hong Kong
and Macao.
</P>
<P>
Of the figure, the number of tourists who stay in China for
more than one day reached 23.77 million, up 4.4 percent. The
tourism index still ranks sixth in the world after France, the
United States, Spain, Italy, and Britain, the World Tourism
Organization said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 7.43 million foreigners visited the Chinese mainland
last year, up 10.1 percent. The number of Hong Kong and Macao
tourists reached 47.94 million, representing a year-on-year rise
of 12.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
China earned 12.07 billion U.S. dollars from overseas tourists
last year, up 18.4 percent, climbing to eighth place in the world
after the US, Italy, Spain, France, Britain, Germany and Austria.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference today, He Guangwei, chairman of
the China National Tourism Administration (CNTA), said this showed
the success of Visit China '97, a state-level tourism promotion.
</P>
<P>
In 1997 the CNTA hosted the annual meeting of the Pacific-Asia
Travel Association (PATA) and a series of activities to celebrate
the return of Hong Kong to the motherland. In addition, 35 famous
scenic spots, 16 tourist itineraries, and 48 tourism festivals
were put forward to lure foreign visitors.
</P>
<P>
The number of domestic tourists reached 644 million last year,
earning the country 211.27 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Smuggled Drugs Destroyed in Kampala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Smuggled drugs worth of 109
million Uganda Shillings (some 95,000 U.S. Dollars) have been
destroyed Wednesday in Kampala, The New Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The drugs destroyed include 2.93 kilogram of heroine worth of
102 million Shillings and 102 grams of cocaine worth of 20
million Shillings.
</P>
<P>
They were confiscated last year from six traffickers in the
country. One involved in the trafficking has been fined, and the
other traffickers have been detained and now are serving their
terms in prisons.
</P>
<P>
The narcotics have been destroyed under the supervision of
police and other officials of the city.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is considered by criminals as an intermediate station
in their smuggle lines from Latin America to South Africa and
west Europe in recent years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
