<HEADLINE> Nigeria Backs Peaceful End of U.S.-Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has warned of the
humanitarian effects any military attack by the United States
would have on innocent Iraqis and expressed readiness to support
a peaceful resolution of the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We believe in a peaceful resolution of the crisis," Minister
of State for Foreign Affairs Alhaji Buhari Bala said in the
capital Abuja Wednesday at a meeting with visiting Iraqi
Ambassador Taha Tachar Mohammed.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time Nigeria made public its stand on the
face-off between Iraq and the United States over the inspection
of sites for weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, Nigeria would not support any
country that manufactured trouble for its sake.
</P>
<P>
Whatever offence Iraq committed did not warrant military
action by any country without the mandate of the United Nations
Security Council, he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned the humanitarian effects of American attack as well
as its dire implication to world peace, the official daily New
Nigerian reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
While calling on the international community to ease up the
present sanction on Iraq, the minister said Nigeria will continue
to support Iraq within the framework of the United Nations
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi envoy, according to the report, was in Abuja to
solicit the support of Nigeria for a peaceful resolution of the
crisis, with a letter to that effect from his government to
Nigeria.  
</P>
</TEXT>
