<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Needs 23,000 Information Workers by 2002 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Companies with the
Multimedia Super Corridor (MSC) status in Malaysia will need some
23,000 knowledge workers in the year 2002, with 59 percent of them
in the information technology (IT) field, according to a survey.
</P>
<P>
For this year, the MSC-status companies require 6,728 knowledge
workers, according to the findings of a survey by the Multimedia
Development Corporation (MDC), which were distributed in
conjunction with the 2nd two-day MSC's International Advisory
Panel (IAP) Meeting starting in Cyberjaya near here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The IAP meeting, chaired by Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad and attended by several of the world's top information
technology (IT) chiefs, would discuss issues pertaining to the
development of the MSC and the IT/multimedia industry.
</P>
<P>
MDC Executive Chairman Othman Yeop Abdullah will give an update
on the MSC to the IAP members who would also be briefed by four
MSC-status companies on their operations.
</P>
<P>
Issues to be deliberated during the meeting include global
market trends in IT and cross-border issues such as the future of
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
The 44-member IAP, comprising multimedia industry leaders and
gurus, was formed to advise the Malaysian government on the MSC, a
750 square kilometer area, stretching from the Kuala Lumpur City
Center (KLCC) southwards to the new Kuala Lumpur International
Airport in Sepang, designated as a hub for the development of
multimedia products and services.
</P>
<P>
A total of 103 companies have so far been granted the MSC
status, with 80 already operating and 23 setting up their
operations.
</P>
<P>
According to the MDC which oversees the overall development of
the MSC project, the projected demand for knowledge workers next
year is 9,627, 12,616 for 2000 and 15,488 in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The survey also showed that the supply of knowledge workers in
the country would be more than sufficient to meet the needs of the
MSC as more than 25,000 workers would be available in the market
by 2002.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian Ministry of Education has allocated 5 million
ringgit (1.4 million U.S. dollars) to produce 1,780 master
trainers and conduct IT courses for 30,000 trained primary and
secondary school teachers.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has also allocated 50 million ringgit (14 million
dollars) this year towards the development of Smart Schools.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
