<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Backs Diplomacy on Iraq: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, a non-permanent member
of the U.N. Security Council, wants all diplomatic channels
exhausted before any other steps to resolve the U.S.-Iraq crisis,
Foreign Minister Bonaya Godana said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, he declined to clarify whether Kenya was willing to
provide important logistical support to a U.S.-led force as it
did in the 1991 Gulf War, local press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I don't think we have got to that stage," he said, stressing
the role of the U.N. as a guarantor of world peace and the need
to respect its resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We must exhaust diplomacy before anybody thinks of
alternative approaches to resolve this conflict," he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1991, Kenya's airports and the port of Mombasa provided
vital support for a multinational force which pushed Saddam
Hussein's forces out of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
With the drums of war beating again over Iraq, the U.S. has
mounted a vigorous campaign to mobilize international support for
a possible military operation.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson, the U.S. ambassador to the U.N. and Marine
Corps General Anthony Zinni, commander of U.S. forces in the
Middle East, have visited Nairobi in the past month for talks
with President Daniel arap Moi.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times newspaper Thursday issued an editorial
charging that the U.S. administration "has an unhealthy attitude"
to the current Gulf crisis. The newspaper is run by the ruling
Kenya African National Union (KANU).
</P>
<P>
"The question of whether the U.S. has a right to behave as if
it was the world's policeman has been raised many times over by
U.S. critics from all corners of the globe," noted the editorial.
</P>
<P>
"The critics say America has no authority to control the
manner in which Iraq should conduct its self-defence policies nor
the kind of weapons it chooses to have in its arsenal," it
continued.
</P>
<P>
"Another explosion of violence in the Gulf region is something
few countries in the world would want to see," it concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
