<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 09:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaitis Cope With Iraq Crisis, Reactions Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti government has
been stepping up preparation for a possible Iraqi retaliation if
U.S. military strikes against Iraq come true, but Kuwaitis have
shown mixed reactions to the current escalating crisis.
</P>
<P>
Some Kuwaitis expressed alarm at the military build-up and
preparations for a possible military confrontation in the region,
while many others carried on with their daily work without any
noticeable change.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain have amassed a major military presence in
the Gulf and said military deployment for the attacks will be
completed in a week or so from now.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz indicated Wednesday
that Iraq will not retaliate at Kuwait if it comes under
U.S. attack, saying Baghdad did not have any plans or intentions
to strike anybody "except the aggressors."
</P>
<P>
However, Kuwait has put its 16,000 armed forces on high alert
and mobilized its 24,000 reserves. "Patriot" missiles are deployed
in strategic sites to guard against any missile attack from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has also taken several civil precautionary measures,
including importing gas masks, encouraging reserve donations to
blood banks, outlining contingency plans to distribute essential
foodstuffs and to guarantee water and electricity supplies.
</P>
<P>
It has also issued safety guidelines to the public and steps to
follow in case of a chemre preparing sealed or underground rooms in
their homes stocked with basic food, water, medicines and
charcoal enough for one-month or more as anti-chemical or
biological weapons shelters.
</P>
<P>
But life remains normal. A foreign diplomat here said "a high
level of nervousness in Kuwait is seen, but it is not panic."
</P>
<P>
The majority of Kuwaitis have abstained from stockpiling food
supplies as the authorities assured the people that there was no
need for panic.
</P>
<P>
People are taking advantage of the early spring season to
marry. Wedding ceremonies are being held everywhere in the country
during the night when relatives and friends go to extend their
good wishes to the new couples in well-lit Arabic traditional
tents.
</P>
<P>
"Latest developments require certain preparations but within
reason and in line with guidelines carried on newspapers and
broadcast by the media," a Kuwaiti said.
</P>
<P>
"Kuwait is OK, and the military preparations are assuring,"
his friend added, emphasizing that there was no need to store
large amounts of food supplies.
</P>
<P>
In addition, analysts here said, Kuwait is not involved in what
may be developing into a new military confrontation this time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
