<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Fueling Growth In China's Hydro-electric Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China has 23 hydropower
projects in operation or under construction by utilizing foreign
funds worth nearly 3.7 billion US dollars, with a total generating
capacity over 18.84 million kw.
</P>
<P>
"China has the richest hydro-electric power resources in the
world, with exploitable water energy resources estimated at 376
million kw, ranking first in the world," said Zhao Xizheng,
vice-minister of the electric power industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhao says that China has completed 13 hydropower projects with
a combined generating capacity of 5.62 million kw by using 1.44
billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Five others, with a total capacity of 8.1 million kw, are being
built with 1.4 billion US dollars worth of foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
China has been developing its hydro-electric power industry for
four decades, but especially since the reforms and opening-up
drive began in 1979.
</P>
<P>
Total generating capacity and annual electricity output have
risen from 163,000 kw and 710 million kwh respectively, in 1949,
to today's 52.17 million kw and 186.8 billion kwh. This makes
China third in generating capacity and production in the world.
</P>
<P>
However, Zhao says, there is still a lot that needs to be done
to make use of China's enormous resources. Its total generating
capacity accounts for only 13.8 percent of what is possible.
</P>
<P>
According to China's medium- and long-range development plans,
it will have a capacity of 70 million kw by the year 2000, and by
2010, that will rise to 125 million kw, or 33.1 percent of the
country's exploitable hydro-electric power resources.
</P>
<P>
Zhao says that 3.5 million kw will be added annually, on
average, in the remaining years of the century, and from 2000 to
2010, hydro-electric power capacity will increase by five million
kw annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
