<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing To Release Weekly Urban Air Quality Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing plans to follow the
example of 27 other Chinese cities in releasing weekly urban air
quality reports for the general public, director of the National
Environmental Protection Agency (NEPA), Xie Zhenhua, told a press
conference today.
</P>
<P>
The municipal government in China's capital is placing great
emphasis on environmental protection, and although nitrogen
levels have risen since the 1980s because of the increase in the
number of automobiles, sulfur levels have remained the same, and
the amount of suspended particles has been declining.
</P>
<P>
According to a 41-week NEPA study, the city's air quality was
quite good for ten weeks in the summer, with slight pollution for
16 weeks; medium pollution for 14 weeks, and seriously pollution
for only one week.
</P>
<P>
An irrational industrial structure, rapid urban development,
and a growing population are all causes of growing environmental
pressures. There are more than 4,000 construction sites around the
city, which has grown 28 percent in size.
</P>
<P>
The weekly report will have an atmospheric pollution index for
sulfur dioxide, oxygen and nitrogen compounds, and amount of
suspended particles.
</P>
<P>
Major cities like Nanjing, Shanghai, and Wuhan have provided
these reports in the local media since last May. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
