<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Current Account Surplus Posts First Rise in Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan's current account surplus
in 1997 rose for the first time in four years from a year earlier,
up 59.8 percent to 11,435.7 billion yen (793 billion
U.S. dollars), the Finance Ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the increase to the strong growth in
exports, which outpaced increases in imports and a decline in
services trade reflecting fewer Japanese tourists traveling abroad.
</P>
<P>
Exports climbed by 13.7 percent to 49,517.2 billion yen (402
billion dollars), while imports rose by 7.9 percent to 37,188.0
billion yen (302 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
In goods and services trading, Japan registered a surplus of
5,803.1 billion yen (47 billion dollars), up 150.4 percent from a
year before, the ministry said in a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The surplus in merchandise trade grew by 35.5 percent to
12,329.1 billion yen (100 billion dollars), the first increase in
five years.
</P>
<P>
In services trade, including tourism, Japan posted a deficit of
6,526.0 billion yen (53 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The current account balance measures the flow of goods and
services as well as investment and other monetary transfers.
</P>
<P>
For the month of December, Japan's current account surplus rose
by 57.4 percent from a year earlier to 1,295.6 billion yen (11.52
billion dollars), following a 91.8 percent jump in November.
</P>
<P>
The average exchange rate was 129.47 yen to the dollar in
December, compared with 113.81 yen a year earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
