<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Madrid to Remit $600m Debt on Portuguese-Speaking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Portugal would cut off the 600
million U.S. Dollar debt on five Portuguese-speaking countries in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to a report issued by the Organization of Economic
Co-operation and Development (OECD), the debt remission has
resulted in a gradual reduction in Portugal's development aid to
OECD, cutting it from the 258 million dollars in 1995 to the 218
million dollar in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Portugal has promised to keep its development aid to OECD at a
level of 0.36 percent of its Gross Domestic Product (GDP).
</P>
<P>
Portugal, which shares the same language with five African
countries like Angola, Mozambique, Sao Tom &AMP; Principe, Guinea
Bissau and Cape Verde, would strengthen its cooperation with the
five countries in education and in their effort to eliminate
illiteracy.
</P>
<P>
The OECD report said that though Portugal is trying to enlarge
its cooperation scale, these five former colonies are still the
main target in its foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the biggest challenge Portugal is facing
is Angola and Mozambique, which need huge international aid in
their reconstruction after wars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
