<HEADLINE> Zambia's Tourism onto Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- A private company, Africa
Insites, has been set up in Lusaka to offer information on
tourism in Zambia on the Internet, according to a local
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The company which has already won approval by the Zambia
National Tourist Board and the Tourism Council of Zambia will
focus on comprehensive and up-to date information relating to
tourism, business and travel in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Post today quoted the firm's chief executive Robyn Curtis
as saying Wednesday that his company has set up a web guide on
Zambia comprising 200 pages with information ranging from
business to local culture.
</P>
<P>
"The information is supplemented by stunning color photos and
adverts of local tourism products and packages," said Curtis.
</P>
<P>
The company will operate on earnings derived from adverts
placed by tour operators, lodges and hotels whose brochures can
be advertised on the web guide.
</P>
<P>
The paper also quoted Africa Insites spokesman Jifipa Ngalande
as saying Wednesday in an interview that response from
advertisers have been overwhelming with some adverts being from
South Africa and England.
</P>
<P>
He said the initiative has been taken following complaints
about the difficulties of accessing information on Zambia from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
The advertising rates have been pegged at 250 U.S Dollars for
the whole year with incentives such as making amendments to the
running adverts when necessary, Curtis disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Africa Insites also offers companies and individuals with
their own web sites to be part of the information package by
listing them, at a cost of 100 dollars, in an appropriate section
to enable users get linked to their sites.
</P>
<P>
The firm's spokesman added that more and more people are using
the Internet to decide where to go on holiday and Zambia needs a
good web site to compete with the rest of the world as a holiday
destination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
