<HEADLINE> China, Pakistan Hold Investment Forum in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Economic and trade cooperation
between China and Pakistan is still far from fully developed
compared with the economic strength of the two countries and the
growth of bilateral political relations, Chinese Vice-Premier Wu
Bangguo told a Sino-Pakistan investment forum here today.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif also attended
the meeting and spoke.
</P>
<P>
The Conference on Investment Opportunities in Pakistan was
jointly held by the China Council for Promotion of International
Trade (CCPIT) and the Pakistani government.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the forum, Wu said that leaders of the two countries
Wednesday held fruitful talks and signed many important agreements
on cooperative projects. Today's forum is a major activity that
Prime Minister Sharif attended during his visit to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wu expressed the belief that Sharif's visit and the investment
forum will further promote economic and trade cooperation between
the two countries and lay a solid foundation for Sino-Pakistani
friendship for generations.
</P>
<P>
Wu said that in the past 47 years since the two countries
established diplomatic relations, they have conducted fruitful
cooperation in the fields of culture, science, technology, economy
and trade. He said that Pakistan has become a major trade partner
of China in South Asia, and that the momentum of two-way trade has
increased year by year.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that economic and trade cooperation between
the two countries is insufficient compared with their economic
strength and the pace of development of bilateral political
relations.
</P>
<P>
Wu said he believed that joint efforts by the governments and
people of the two countries would result in further consolidation
and development of the partnership of comprehensive cooperation
between China and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He said the Chinese Government will continue to encourage
Chinese companies and enterprises to expand their cooperation with
their Pakistan colleagues.
</P>
<P>
Sharif told the forum that at present, both Pakistan and China
are focusing on expanding their economies. He said the Pakistani
government invites Chinese businesses to become involved in
Pakistan's economic development drive. He said that this is in
conformity with the time-tested friendship that "has always been
the hallmark of Pakistan-China relations."
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people from China and Pakistan attended the
forum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
