<HEADLINE> Australia Intensifies Diplomatic Solution to Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Minister
Alexander Downer said Thursday Australia was intensifying its
diplomatic efforts for peacefully resolving the crisis between the
United States and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Downer said he had asked Australia's Ambassador to the United
Nations Penny Wensley to reinforce Australia's support for a
diplomatic solution to other missions in New York where she is
based.
</P>
<P>
Downer's peace appeal came two days after Australian Prime
Minister John Howard's announcement of Australia's support for any
United States-led military operation against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Howard said Tuesday Australia still hopes military action will
not be necessary, but "If it does become necessary for a United
States-led coalition to use force then Australia has decided it
will make a contribution to that effort."
</P>
<P>
Downer said he had also asked key Australian representatives
around the world to intensify their contact with the concerned
governments and relevant international organizations.
</P>
<P>
"The government is now intensifying its diplomatic efforts to
try to encourage an appropriate and peaceful solution to the
crisis with Iraq," Downer was quoted by the Australian Associated
Press (AAP) as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Australian government's position has been under criticism
from politicians, charity groups and some other organizations.
</P>
<P>
Demonstrations or protests against war against Iraq will be
held in four major Australian cities Friday -- Sydney, Melbourne,
Canberra and Perth, capital of the coastal state of West
Australia, the AAP said.
</P>
<P>
An anti-Gulf War demonstration will be held at the U.S.
Consulate in Sydney Friday, the news agency said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
