<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Trade Union Threatens to Stage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe Congress of Trade
Unions (ZCTU) Wednesday said it will call a two-day national work
boycott on February 27 unless the government scraps 2.5 percent
increase in sales tax.
</P>
<P>
The tax are levied on goods and services, the development levy
and restore prices of basic commodities to pre-July 1997 levels.
</P>
<P>
ZCTU President Gibson Sibanda told more than 4,000 workers who
packed the large City Hall of Bulawayo, the country's second
largest city Wednesday evening that the organization had already
written to the government advising it of its intention to call
for a mass stayaway on February 27 if its demands were not met.
</P>
<P>
He said last December's countrywide mass protests which led to
the withdrawal of the proposed war veterans levy were the
beginning of the "ultimate goal of the liberation of workers"
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
A statement released at the meeting said the major reason why
the country was not realizing its full potential was that
political consideration were over-riding rational economic
thinking.
</P>
<P>
"The political leadership has lost direction as it is mainly
concerned with preserving its power base through corruption to
the extent that it has relegated sound economic advise," it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
