<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Performing Sea Lions at Aquarium Traumatized by Fireworks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Three sea lions, frightened by
the huge noise from firecrackers on the eve of the Chinese lunar
new year, have refused to perform in this port city in east
China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
On Jan. 27, the four South American sea lions in the Dolphin
Hall at the Qingdao Aquarium got a big scare from noisy
firecrackers nearby which were among those allowed by city
authorities to set off firecrackers and fireworks.
</P>
<P>
After 10 days of treatment, one male sea lion has fully
recovered and been able to perform. However, the other three sea
lions have been so scared that, in addition to refusing to return
to the perorming stage, are experiencing physical symptoms such
as shuddering, roaring and diarrhea. They also hide in the water
when they hear any loud noise. And sometimes they refuse to eat.
</P>
<P>
Firecrackers and fireworks have been an integral part of the
new year celebrations and other occasions over the centuries
despite the inevitable fires and injuries.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, firecrackers and fireworks have been banned in
the downtown area in most of China's major cities, with the
exception of a few spots during the Spring Festival in some cities
such as Shanghai, Beijing and Qingdao. For many, it is too
important to be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
In the Chinese capital, authorities have reiterated the ban on
firecrackers and fireworks in the whole downtown area, since the
occurrence of fires and injuries from illegal fireworks during
this year's holiday were the highest since Beijing barred fire
crackers and fireworks five years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
