<HEADLINE> Mugabe Reaffirms Land Reform Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean government will
consider alternative ideas being offered to effectively deal with
the land acquisition programe, but will not accept anything that
will adversely affect its principal position on the issue,
President Robert Mugabe said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing hundreds of ruling ZANU (PF) supporters at the
party headquarters in Harare, Mugabe said, "we can not allow any
proposal to diminish the thrust for acquiring the size of land we
have stipulated as necessary for land acquisition."
</P>
<P>
Last year, the government announced to acquire about 1,500
farms or five million hectares for the resettlement exercise.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe has said the government would not compensate farmers
for land, but for improvements only.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told his supporters, "the responsibility for
compensation is for the former colonial master. They should go
to Britain for that because we are not going back. This is not
politicking."
</P>
<P>
"We have neither a moral or legal obligation to pay them," he
said, adding, "Britain did not pay for that land, so they should
not renege on their obligation".
</P>
<P>
Mugabe made the remarks when he was commenting on the
Commercial Farmers Union (CFU) alternative resettlement plan
which would pave the way for farmers to release large tracts of
land.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-member CFU unveiled an alternative plan after the
government announced its intention to acquire more than 1,500
farms for the resettlement exercise.
</P>
<P>
The CFU offered to release 1.5 million hectares of land now
and source about 15 billion Zimbabwean dollars (about 900 million
U.S. dollars) for the program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
