<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Russia Sign Six agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rome, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Italy and Russia signed six
industrial agreements here Wednesday in the presence of Russian
President Boris Yeltsin and Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
One agreement was signed between Fiat and Gorky Automobile
Factory (Gaz) to launch a joint venture to produce Fiat cars
starting at the end of the year at Nizhni Novgorod (formerly
Gorky), 450 kilometers east of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
The project will cost about 1.55 trillion lire (some 870
million U.S. dollars) and is expected to create 4,000 jobs for the
Russians.
</P>
<P>
Fiat is the first Western industrial group to set up a
production site in Russia. Its Managing Director Paolo Cantarella
said after the signing ceremony, "for us, the deal represents a
great opportunity. We're moving into a country seeing astounding
economic growth."
</P>
<P>
Italy's energy and chemicals group Eni, and Gazprom, the
Russian gas giant, signed an initial agreement for gas and oil
exploration.
</P>
<P>
Technimont, part of the chemical and energy group Montedison,
signed an agreement with Ipolymer to build polypropylene plants in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
Giorgio Fossa, leader of the Italian industrialists'
association Confindustria, said that these deals involving
car-makers and energy groups would "break the ice" and pave the
way for other accords with Italian small and medium businesses.
</P>
<P>
He said, "The year of 1998 could mark a real turnaround for
Italian businesses operating in Russia."
</P>
<P>
In line with another deal, Breda will begin to produce buses
for the Russian city of St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
Merloni Electrodomestics also signed an agreement with the
Russians to invest 100 million dollars in building a home
appliance factory at Friazino near Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the Italian Trade Institute, Russia's ExpoCenter and
Italy's trade fair organizations will collaborate on the
construction of an Italian pavilion at the Moscow Trade Fair.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin told Italian businessmen that they will always be
welcome in Russia. "With our commitment, you will always find the
door open and a guarantee of success in our country."
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that the accords laid the foundation of "reciprocal
economic dependence" on the basis of which the economies of Italy
and Russia would become complementary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
