<HEADLINE> China Sees Good Future For Economic Cooperation With Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's International Trade
News quotes Guo Zhong, of China's Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, as saying that China's rapid economic growth
and the importance attached by the European Union to China
relations mean that there is a bright future for Sino-European
economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Guo, who is in charge of Sino-European trade at the ministry's
European Affairs Department, says that Chinese customs statistics
show that Sino-European trade amounted to 43 billion US dollars in
1997, a 8.3 percent increase from 1996.
</P>
<P>
By September, 1997, there were 8,022 projects in China funded
by EU member countries, involving 30 billion US dollars worth of
investment. China imported 5,030 technology projects from the EU,
worth 35.25 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
China and the EU has been cooperating in industry, energy,
environmental protection, and other sectors.
</P>
<P>
To date, EU member countries and their financial institutions
have extended 12.34 billion US dollars in government loans to
China.
</P>
<P>
Guo says that EU countries had economic growth last year and
the increased exports were a driving force behind that growth
because their governments continued their tightened financial
policies to help reach their goal of a unified currency.
</P>
<P>
The development of economic and trade with China is in their
interest, and China is willing to work together with them for
this, he says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
