<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daehlie Wins 10km Classical Cross Country Skiing (reopens) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian Bjoern Daehlie
defeated bad weather and other medal contenders to win the men's 10km
classical cross country skiing at the 18th Olympic Winter Games here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian, the most successful cross country skiier in history,
was timed 27 minutes and 24.5 seconds in a steady rain.
</P>
<P>
Markus Gandler of Austria was second with eight seconds behind and
Italian Mika Myllylae, gold medal winner in Monday's 30km classical
race, was third with further 15.6 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
National hero Daehlie, who finished a disappointing 20th in the
men's 30km, led at every split of the race and collapsed in exhaustion
at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
It was the sixth Olympic gold medal for the Norwegian, who also won
the event in Lillehammer, Norway four years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Daehlie is still waiting for his seventh Olympic gold, a
record in Winter Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, the victory today is fantastic, but I think I will
appreciate it more in a few years when I'm a grandfather and watching
old videos," the 30-year-old skiier said.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie had trained hard in his career. In his 1997 autobiography,
he estimated that he covered 150,000 kilometers on skis, foot or
cycling over the previous decade --the equivalent of alomost four
trips round the world.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy with the race today," he added.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie credited his victory to his mother, who gave some advice
after the 30km race.
</P>
<P>
"She said that I think you have forgotten something," the Norwegian
recalled. "It's to go a little bit faster than the others. Then you
will win."
</P>
<P>
Myllylae believed that mistakes in choosing correct skis and wax
caused his gold today.
</P>
<P>
"We had some problems in choosing skis and grip wax today," he
said. "But there were many skiiers that had the same problems. Many
skiiers were running away from the track."
</P>
<P>
Philip Boit, the only athlete from Kenya who makes debut at Winter
Olympics, managed to finish the race and came in the last at 47:25.5.
</P>
<P>
"My aim is to compete here and learn from others," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Summer Palace Nominated for UNESCO World Heritage List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Roland Silva, chairman of
UNESCO's Council of International Historical Sites and Ruins, is
doing a study of the Summer Palace in Beijing, which has been
nominated for inclusion on the World Heritage List.
</P>
<P>
The Summer Palace, located in the northwestern part of Beijing,
is China's largest imperial garden, attracting 40-to-50 million
visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
The palace was first built in 1750 by the government of the
Qing Dynasty. Then it was destroyed twice, first by British and
French soldiers in 1860 and then by troops jointly sent by Great
Britain, the United States, Germany, France, tsarist Russia,
Japan, Italy and Austria in 1900.
</P>
<P>
The palace was renovated in 1902, and became a public garden in
1924.
</P>
<P>
After new China was founded in 1949 the buildings, relics,
plants, hills and lakes were put under national
protection. Today's Summer Palace covers an area of 290 hectares,
with the water area accounting for three quarters of that.
</P>
<P>
More than 40,000 relics are housed in the Summer Palace,
ranging from the bronzeware of the Shang Dynasty (1600-1100 BC) to
the handicrafts of the late Qing Dynasty (1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
The park has set up files for the relics, as well as 70,000
square meters of ancient buildings and 1,622 trees more than 200
years old.
</P>
<P>
Each year some of the ancient buildings will be repaired
according to the plans drawn up by experts and approved by
cultural relics departments. Related departments have also drafted
regulations on the buildings' position, color, height and material
surrounding the Summer Palace.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has applied for the inclusion of the
Summer Palace and the Temple of Heaven on the World Heritage List
of the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural
Organization. So far, China has 19 sites on the list, including
the Great Wall and the Forbidden City.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
