<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese City Leading Country in Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The capital of China's
Guangdong Province reported a GDP of 164.3 billion yuan in 1997,
an increase that, at 13.5 percent, was higher than both the
national and provincial average.
</P>
<P>
Consumer goods did more than 80.3 billion yuan in business last
year, a year-on-year increase of 16.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the city has used more than 2.5 billion US
dollars worth of overseas investment in real terms annually, and
expects to see more coming in.
</P>
<P>
For the last two decades, Guangzhou has tried different forms
of ownership and tried many forms of economy and now, the private
sector has come to account for 30 percent of its economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The city's Party Secretary Gao Siren says the good economy
comes from the market economy and the law of value, as well as the
introduction of shares to its enterprise reforms early in 1985.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Guangzhou raised 60 to 70 billion yuan for
infrastructure and urban construction over the past few years, one
third of which came from overseas sources.
</P>
<P>
The city has tried every possible means of attracting foreign
investment, but economic and technological development zones are
one of the favorites. The Guangzhou Economic Development Zone, for
example, has grown to a 20-billion-yuan annual output level and
provides 2.3 billion yuan in revenues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
