<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Get Into Offshore Banking Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Starting this year, China will
launch off-shore banking business, Shanghai Securities News
reports today.
</P>
<P>
The new business was first tried out in the Shenzhen Special
Economic Zone, Guandong Province, in 1989 and was a significant
step forward in China's effort to improve its financial system,
prevent financial risks, and increase reforms, the newspaper says.
</P>
<P>
It quotes Mao Yingliang, the governor of the Shanghai Branch of
the People's Bank of China, the central bank, as saying that
Shanghai will begin its offshore banking business this
year. Shanghai's municipal government has decided to start it in
the Pudong New Area, a finance and trade zone separated from the
city proper by the Huangpu River.
</P>
<P>
It will try to make the most of Pudong's openness to form an
offshore financial market and speed up the process of turning
Shanghai into an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
After several years of experimentation, China has a fairly
complete set of administrative rules for the offshore financial
business, which includes foreign currency deposits and loans,
international settlements, foreign exchange guarantees, interbank
foreign currency borrowing and lending, and large deposit
transfers.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that Shanghai generally has all the right
conditions needed for the offshore financial business. It is
China's economic and financial center and has a concentration of
overseas financial institutions and is home to China's national
foreign exchange trading and one of its two stock exchanges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
