<HEADLINE> 800 Women Apply to Join Sri Lankan Air Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, February 12 (Xinhua) -- About 800 women have applied
to join the Sri Lankan Air Force (SLAF) and fly over war-zones
since the SLAF began to recruit women pilots last November, chief
recruiting officer J. Ranasinghe said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said 33 candidates had already been selected and they will
be trained at the Air Force Flying Training School in
Anuradhapura, North Central Province, for two years.
</P>
<P>
Ranasinghe said they will receive the same training as the male
trainees.
</P>
<P>
Besides initial interviews the candidates had already gone
through, they will have to undergo an officer quality test, an
aptitude test, a medical test and a final interview, he said.
</P>
<P>
Once becoming pilots, they need to serve the Air Force for 12
years and will only be allowed to leave the service under the
directive of the president.
</P>
<P>
Depending on the vacancies, more women candidates could be
called in the future, Ranasinghe said.
</P>
<P>
The decision to recruit women pilots was made after the SLAF
failed to recruit enough male pilots to fill the vacancies left by
the loss of dozens of pilots in plane crashes.
</P>
<P>
The Air Force has lost at least 19 planes and helicopters,
including four warplanes and attack helicopters, in the past two
and a half years.
</P>
<P>
Until now, the SLAF has employed women only in ground roles,
mainly for office work.  
</P>
</TEXT>
