<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Daehlie Wins 10km Classical Cross Country Skiing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Norwegian Bjoern Daehlie
defeated bad weather and other medal contenders to win the men's 10km
classical cross country skiing at the 18th Olympic Winter Games here
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian, the most successful cross country skiier in history,
was timed 27 minutes and 24.5 seconds in a steady rain.
</P>
<P>
Markus Gandler of Austria was second with eight seconds behind and
Italian Mika Myllylae, gold medal winner in Monday's 30km classical
race, was third with further 15.6 seconds behind.
</P>
<P>
National hero Daehlie, who finished a disappointing 20th in the
men's 30km, led at every split of the race and collapsed in exhaustion
at the finish line.
</P>
<P>
It was the fifth Olympic gold medal for the Norwegian, who also won
the event in Lillehammer, Norway four years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Daehlie is still waiting for his sixth Olympic gold, a
record in Winter Olympic history.
</P>
<P>
"Of course, the victory today is fantastic, but I think I will
appreciate it more in a few years when I'm a grandfather and watching
old videos," the 30-year-old skiier said.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie had trained hard in his career. In his 1997 autobiography,
he estimated that he covered 150,000 kilometers on skis, foot or
cycling over the previous decade --the equivalent of alomost four
trips round the world.
</P>
<P>
"I am very happy with the race today," he added.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie credited his victory to his mother, who gave some advice
after the 30km race.
</P>
<P>
"She said that I think you have forgotten something," the Norwegian
recalled. "It's to go a little bit faster than the others. Then you
will win."
</P>
<P>
Myllylae believed that mistakes in choosing correct skis and wax
caused his gold today.
</P>
<P>
"We had some problems in choosing skis and grip wax today," he
said. "But there were many skiiers that had the same problems. Many
skiiers were running away from the track." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Discontinue Advancing Foreign Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided to discontinue advancing its foreign debt payments and
will carefully weigh the pros and cons of a proposal to reschedule
the country's foreign debts, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a parliament hearing Wednesday, Finance Minister
Mar'ie Muhammad said Indonesia's foreign debt payments due in
fiscal 1998/99 were projected to total 37.8 trillion rupiah (5.18
billion U.S. dollar), excluding the amount of prepayments.
</P>
<P>
"Basically, the government always tries to service its foreign
debts on time. Therefore, we must carefully weigh the pros and
cons of any proposal to reschedule those debts. We have to
maintain our credibility internationally," local press reports
Thursday quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's foreign debts as of December 31, 1997
totaled 63.5 billion dollars, of which 54.2 billion dollars were
direct government debts and 9.3 billion dollars state-owned
companies' debts.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, all the foreign debts were free from
political strings, carried low interest rates and were generally
repayable over a minimum period of 10 years.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's foreign debts differed from the
private sector's in that they were long-term and carried lower
rates of interest.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's private sector's foreign debts totaled 73.962
billion dollars at the end of December last year. Economists here
held that the private sector's debts were one of the main causes
for the depreciation of the Indonesian rupiah against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has lost more than 60 percent of its value against
the dollar since July last year.
</P>
<P>
Mar'ie admitted that to meet the needs of future investment,
the government would continue to require foreign loans but it was
determined to pursue a prudent foreign borrowing policy.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the future debts of the government and
state-owned companies would not be made for consumptive purposes
but for productive, high-value and export-oriented projects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
