<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korean Stock Prices Plunging Amid Possible Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The Seoul stock market dropped
about three percent and the won depreciated to 1,600 against the U.S.
dollar this morning amid a possibility of massive labor strike.
</P>
<P>
The composite index plumeted more than 20 points to below 500
points a few minutes after 10 a.m. Thursday, but recovered slightly to
506.50 as of 11 a.m., 13.64 points lower than Wednesday's close.
</P>
<P>
The composite index soared to over 550 points and the won
appreciated to 1,500 against the U.S. dollar at the end of last month
when South Korea reached an agreement with major creditor countries to
delay the payment of the nation's debts totaling 154 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the stock market began to show a downward trend Monday
because the Korean Confederation of Trade Unions (KCTU), which formed
a new leadership after ousting their leaders responsible for signing
on Monday, threatened to stage a general strike to boycott a layoff
agreement reached by the representatives from labor, capital and the
government.
</P>
<P>
The representatives signed the agreement to legalize mass layoffs
in return for more labor freedom last Friday following hard
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, capital could dismiss workers only when they
face "emergency situation" as as financial trouble, merger or
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
The confederation Tuesday warned that a strike couldn't be avoided
unless the government went back to the negotiation table for another
round of talks to hammer out a new layoff accord.
</P>
<P>
But, the government Wednesday answered that there could not be any
form of renegotiation, saying that it could not tolerate illegal union
acts and would deal hard with strikes staged by labor unions.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has warned of a possible
recurrence of the foreign currency crisis if South Korean labor unions
walk out.
</P>
<P>
It said large-scale strikes in the course of corporate
restructuring will immediately hurt foreign sentiment for investments,
likely bringing a new round of financial crisis to the country, which
has been in a serious financial crisis caused by corporate failures
and bad loans of financial institutions since late 1997.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed with the IMF last December for a rescue
loan of 57 billion U.S. dollars, South Korea has to restructure its
economy, open its financial market and legalize mass layoffs.
</P>
<P>
Analyst said at least one million South Koreans will lose their
jobs this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0266 </DOCNO>
