<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Doubles Minimum Flight Altitude </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 11 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of the recent cable
car disaster, Italy has doubled the minimum altitude at which an
aircraft can fly over the national territory.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations come into effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
Italian Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta, reporting to
parliament Wednesday, said he had given orders to double the
minimum threshold for low-flying flights.
</P>
<P>
This meant raising the lowest possible altitude from 500 to
1,000 feet (151 to 303 meters) over the Po plain and Appennines,
and from 500 to 2,000 feet (151 to 606 meters) throughout the
Italian alpine region. The lowest overflight altitudes for other
countries remains at 1,500 feet (454 meters).
</P>
<P>
The minister has also ordered a review of those areas correctly
set aside for the low-flight training with a view to environmental
impact and safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
Complaint forms have been made available to be used by citizens
or local officials to report hazards or violations of safety norms.
</P>
<P>
Andreatta once again emphasized: "The terrible incident would
not have happened if the rules had been correctly applied and if
the maps regularly supplied to NATO command posts by the Italian
Air Forces had been effectively distributed."
</P>
<P>
A low-flying United States warplane slashed ski-lift cables in
the Dolomites February 3, plunging 20 people in a cable car to
their deaths.
</P>
<P>
Formal contacts have been established with the pertinent office
at the U.S. embassy in Rome to expedite, as quickly as possible,
compensation to the families of the victims, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The plane that brought the cable car down at the Mt. Cermis
resort was flying out of the Aviano base in northeastern Italy,
the biggest U.S. air base in Italy. It is about 90 miles (150
kilometers) southeast of the site of the accident in the Dolomite
range. 
</P>
</TEXT>
