<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ALCA Preparatory Meeting to Seek Consensus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Vice ministers from 34
American countries held their second-day close-door meeting
Wednesday in an effort to reach agreement about negotiations for
establishing a free trade area for the Americas (ALCA).
</P>
<P>
According to sources, participants did not reach any agreement
on the first day about how negotiations are to be handled at ALCA,
its objectives and principles or its headquarters and the
establishment of a permanent secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Canada, Central America and the South
American Common Market (Mercosur) presented various ideas and
concepts for the ALCA structure.
</P>
<P>
Mercosur, which is composed of Brazil, Argentina, Paraguay and
Uruguay, proposed transforming the current 12 working groups into
five negotiating tables that would consist of services,
intellectual property and investment, solution of controversies,
trade disciplines, access to markets and an agrarian sector.
</P>
<P>
But the Central American countries proposed creating 11
negotiating tables.
</P>
<P>
Eduardo Ayala, vice-minister of foreign trade of Costa Rica and
chairman of this preparatory meeting, admitted that the topics of
the meeting are difficult, but all participants were aware that a
satisfactory outcome has to be reached.
</P>
<P>
A consensus document is expected to arise from the three-day
meeting. It will be approved during the March 16-18 meeting here
and presented to the second summit of the Americas on April 16-18
in Santiago, Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
