</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- An earthquake measuring 4.5 on the Richter scale
jolted Ambon, capital of Indonesia's Maluku province and its
surrounding areas at 20:54 local time on Wednesday, the Antara
news agency said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The epicenter of the quake was 45 km beneath the sea, Antara
quoted the Meteorological and Geophysical Office in Ambon as
saying. (Indonesia-Quake)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Inclement weather was hampering relief operations
of the United Nations and other international aid agencies in the
quake-stricken Takhor Province in Northern Afghanistan,
U.N. officials said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is about 20 centimeter snow there and no relief plane
could get into northern Afghanistan," said a U.N. official here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said a relief helicopter from Tajikistan could
only land in the snow-clad Takhor, where more than 4,000 were
killed and many injured in last week's powerful earthquake and
strong aftershocks. (Afghanistan-Quake-Rescue)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton will make his first
visit as president to five African nations from March 22 to April
2, the White House announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the trip will cover
Ghana, Uganda, South Africa, Botswana and Senegal and the main aim
is to highlight the U.S. partnership with Africa and promote
economic relations between the United States and the African
nations. (Clinton-Africa-Visit)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Italy will receive 735 shoulder-fired, U.S.-made
Stinger air defense missiles under a planned sale of 110 million
U.S. dollars, the Defense Department announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Italy, which already has Stringers in its inventory, will use
the missiles to update its air defense capability, a Pentagon said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"This proposed sale will contribute to the foreign policy and
national security objectives of the United States by improving the
military capabilities of Italy while enhancing weapon system
standardization and interoperability," the statement
said. (US-Italy-Missiles)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
TOKYO - Japan's current account surplus in December increased
57.4 percent from a year earlier to 1,295.6 billion yen (about 10
billion U.S. dollars), the finance ministry said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The nation's trade surplus jumped 35.7 percent to 1,416.9
billion yen (11.3 billion dollars) in the month, with exports
climbing 12.2 percent to 4,563.8 billion yen while imports rising
4.1 percent to 3,146.9 billion yen.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Japan's current account surplus surged 59.8 percent to
11,435.7 billion yen. (Japan-Account Surplus)
</P>
