<HEADLINE> Northern Chinese Province Builds Six Chemical Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 12 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
Province is building six chemical production bases over the next
two or three years, a local government official said.
</P>
<P>
Petrolchemical bases will be built in cities of Cangzhou
and Shijiazhuang. In the former, a city combining petrolchemical
production with salt chemical production is being built and the
latter will concentrate on chemical fiber and medicines.
</P>
<P>
Tangshan has been chosen for a salt chemical base that can
expand the existing soda production capacity to 1 million tons
 annually.
</P>
<P>
A coal-related chemical base in Handan will be geared to methyl
alcohol and acetic acid production.
</P>
<P>
The Baoding fine chemical base will develop sensitive film and
related products and a similar base will be built in Xinji for
barium and strontiam.
</P>
<P>
According to a provincial plan, Hebei will raise the ratio of
fine chemical products from the present 21.8 percent to 40 percent
by 2000, and chemical fertilizer output value will drop from 32
percent to no more than 25 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Waive VAT on Purchases by Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to waive
the 10 percent value-added-tax (VAT) on the goods that foreign
tourists buy in Thailand, a local newspaper said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government is expected to issue an executive decree to
legalizing the waiver next month to encourage foreign tourists to
buy goods in Thailand, the Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Deputy finance minister Pichet Phanvichartkul said Thailand
could lose 1.6 billion baht (40 million U.S. dollars) in tax
revenues a year after the waiver takes effect, but the move could
help generate tens of billions of baht from tourism, sales of
goods and employment each year.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Finance Ministry is working on the draft decree which
will be presented to the cabinet for approval late next month.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is pushing ahead the tax waiver plan in a bid to make
the country as a shopping center to catch up with Singapore and
Hong Kong, bringing in more foreign exchanges it badly needs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
