<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy: Military Actions Against Iraq Option </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Military measures against Iraq
are an option if Saddam Hussein keeps refusing access to alleged
weapons sites, Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Italian state radio, Prodi said if the appeal for a
diplomatic solution went unheeded, "non-peaceful weapons remain,
unfortunately."
</P>
<P>
If the United Nations inspections were not "absolutely
transparent", Prodi warned, "it is clear that the conflict cannot
be averted."
</P>
<P>
He said the appeal made with visiting Russian President Boris
Yeltsin on Tuesday lays down a set of precise conditions for
Saddam to respect.
</P>
<P>
The appeal stresses a preference for political rather than
military responses to the stand-off over weapons inspections.
But, Prodi said, "it is accompanied by conditions that absolutely
cannot be avoided."
</P>
<P>
Asked if Italy had informed its traditional allies before
taking the unusual step of making the appeal with Russia, the
Italian prime minister said this initiative was agreed in a
specific way only with Yeltsin, but the allies were informed of it.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that he did not consult United States President
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Prodi stressed that the issue of weapons inspections lay at the
heart of the appeal. Italy and Russia would continue to make
every effort to avert military conflict while working to ensure
all weapons sites were inspected thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said
Wednesday that there was no reason to deny the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization and U.S. the use military bases in Italy as a
contribution to a negotiated solution to the crisis between Iraq
and the U.N.
</P>
<P>
If the bases were unavailable it would help undermine the
credibility of continuing diplomatic efforts to open up suspected
Iraqi sites to the U.N. monitoring teams, Dini said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
