<HEADLINE> 20 Passengers Injured in Train Accident in Rome </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 11 (Xinhua) -- More than 20 passengers were
injured Wednesday when a train departing the Rome central station
was rear-ended by a locomotive.
</P>
<P>
State Railways (FS) officials said the train, bound for Pisa,
was pulling out of the station when a locomotive used to switch
and arrange train cars for transport rammed the rear of the
eight-carriage train.
</P>
<P>
Between 20-25 passengers were taken to the FS first aid
facility in the station or nearby hospitals where they were
treated for cuts and bruises. The most seriously injured
passenger suffered a broken nose, said officials.
</P>
<P>
The train was scheduled to make a stop in the Tyrrhenian port
city of Civitavecchia to connect with a ferry departing for
Sardinia.
</P>
<P>
The departure of the Tirrenia lines ferry was delayed to
accommodate passengers arriving late from Rome.
</P>
<P>
On February 2, a dozen passengers suffered bruises and
superficial injuries when their train, bound for Milan from nearby
Varese, was derailed on the outskirts of the city between the Rho
and Milan Certosa station.
</P>
<P>
The train's two engineers and chief conductor were also injured
in that mishap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
