<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Province's Marine Economy Gets Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The coastal city of Rongcheng
in east China's Shangdong Province has 98 overseas-funded
enterprises involved in the marine economy that have brought in 43
million U.S. dollars worth of investment and have used 39.22
million U.S. dollars, China Township Enterprise Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, it earned 10.5 billion yuan (1.3 billion U.S. dollars)
from its fisheries, 16.7 percent more than for 1996.
</P>
<P>
It has allocated funds for a 200-kilometer coastal highway and
improved water and power supplies. It has also rebuilt four
historic sites to attract Chinese and overseas tourists. It has 90
ports, including two state-level open ports at Shidao and Shiyan.
</P>
<P>
To get more overseas investors, the city has tried to make
service more efficient and to develop preferential policies.
</P>
<P>
To enter the international market, it has estalished trade ties
with Japan, the US, the Republic of Korea, and other
countries. Six aquatic product companies have opened offices and
trading companies in Japan, the US, and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The Qiujia Aquatic Product Group Company alone has offices or
trading companies in Japan, the US, and the Republic of Korea, and
has gotten more than six million U.S. dollars in overseas funds
and built nine joint ventures. It exported 9,850 tons of aquatic
products in 1997, and had foreign exchange earnings of 25 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The local government has treated overseas-funded enterprises as
a major part of its economy, one playing an important role. 
</P>
</TEXT>
