<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal Pictures Help People Find Lost Properties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan
province is famous for its variety of animal species. In its
capital Kunming, animal pictures are helping people retrieve their
properties lost on taxis.
</P>
<P>
The pictures of cute elephants, lions, eagles and others
coupled with a single- or a two-digit number adorn the insides of
all the taxis in the city known as the Spring City. Apart from the
picture, there is a message in both Chinese and English, "The
police suggests that you remember the animal and the number".
</P>
<P>
When a lady came to Kunming for a shopping tour, she left her
purse with 20,000 yuan (about 2,400 US dollars) inside on the
taxi. Fortunately, her intrigued son was able to tell the police
the lion and the corresponding number 78.
</P>
<P>
In two minutes, the police traced the taxi and the 20,000 yuan
soon finds its way back to her, who was overwhelmed with relief
and gratitude.
</P>
<P>
There are nearly 6,000 cabs in Kunming, said Zhang Jun, deputy
police chief of the city. The pictures of 37 commonly known
animals, including elephants, snakes and eagles, are used to mark
the cabs, coupled with numbers from one to 99.
</P>
<P>
Each animal with one number represents two cabs in different
types, explained Zhang, therefore one animal with numbers from 1
to 99 are able to represent 198 taxis, and 37 animals with 99
numbers represent 7,326.
</P>
<P>
For example, if one wants to find a cab with the picture of a
frog and the number 37, a computer operator in the police station
can instantly find out that a frog with 37 represent a Santana and
a Charade, two totally different sedans. Other information shown
on the computer includes their respective plate numbers, colors,
owners, as well as the pictures, ages and addresses of their
drivers.
</P>
<P>
"This differentiation of cabs by animals, which can only be in
Kunming, has greatly convenienced passengers," said Zhang. "People
tend to take little notice of the plate number of the cab they
take, let alone remember it. However, an animal picture with a
single- or two-digit number is interesting to look at and easy to
memorize."
</P>
<P>
Police figures show that the retrieval rate of lost properties
on taxis used to be less than 10 percent, which was about the
national average. Since the animal pictures were introduced last
August, the rate has soared to 43.8 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
