<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC to Co-Operate with Police Probe of Canadian Snowboarder </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- International Olympic
Committee (IOC) is will to cooperate with an investigation by Japanese
police of Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati, who was disqualified
from the games after testing positive for marijuana, an IOC
spokesperson said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"I can see no reason whyIOC would not cooperate with the local
authorities," Michele Verdier said at a joint IOC-NAOC press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Verdier said she did not know if the IOC had already been asked for
help in investigating Rebagliati who was stripped of his giant slalom
gold medal Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rebagliati faces criminal charges if found in possession of
marijuana in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Possession of drugs is illegal in Japan. One police spokesman
said:"We would not give penalty to anyone who takes drugs. But if he
takes it, he must possess it."
</P>
<P>
It was the first drug case that hit the games.
</P>
<P>
IOC Director-General Francois Carrard, who made the announcement
at a press conference on Wednesday, said Canada was appealing against
the decision to disqualify Rebagliati.
</P>
<P>
He said a ruling would be made within 24 hours on the appeal.
</P>
<P>
Marijuana is commonly used as a recreational drug rather than
performance-enhancing substance, but the International Olympic
Committee listed it in the banned substances.
</P>
<P>
Carrard said that metabolized marijuana was detected in an "A"
sample, and then a "B" sample confirmed 17.8 nanograms per milliliter
of the substance.
</P>
<P>
The IOC has no minimum amounts set for substance infractions, but
the International Ski Federation to which Rebagliati is a member sets
15 nanogram limit.
</P>
<P>
Deciding between issuing a warning or sanctions to the snowboarder,
both the medical commission and the IOC Executive Board voted in
favour of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The medical commission voted 13-12 to recommend sanctioning the
snowboarder to the IOC which takes the action. The IOC executive
board voted 3-2 with 2 abstentions on the matter, Carrard said.
</P>
<P>
Italy's Thomas Prugger won the silver medal behind Rebagliati on
Sunday, with Ueli Kestenholz of Switzerland taking bronze and Austrian
Dieter Krassnig finishing fourth. They would move up if the
disqualification is upheld. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
