<HEADLINE> Panamanian Economy Grows in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian economy
grew by 4.4 percent in 1997 over the previous year, Guillermo
Chapman, Minister of Planning and Economical Policy, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chapman said the growth was attributed to Panama's right
financial policy.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that the gross domestic product would be up 5 to
5.5 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Chapman praised the privatizing process undertaken by the
government with the sales of the National Institute of
Telecommunications, the harbors and the Institute for Hydraulic
Resources and Electricity.
</P>
<P>
But the minister said that the production in agriculture was
reduced due to the "El Nino" phenomenon and the Latin-American
banana quotas imposed by the European Union. 
</P>
