<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrest of Serb War Crime Suspect Protested </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Boro Bosich, co-prime
minister of the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, Wednesday
protested the arrest of a Serb war crime suspect by the
Muslim-Croat secret police in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
Bosich, a Serb, in letters to senior members of international
organizations, called for Goran Vasich's release. Vasich had been
arrested on February 6 on charge of killing Haklja Turajlich,
former deputy prime minister of Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
The assassination took place in 1993 at a Serb check point when
a Serb soldier opened fire at Turajlich who was on his way to
war-torn Sarajevo under escort of French peacekeepers. Turajlich
died instantly on the spot.
</P>
<P>
Following the arrest of Vasich, U.N. spokesman Aleksandar
Ivanko told reporters in Sarajevo that Vasich might be sent to the
international tribunal in The Hague for trial.
</P>
<P>
However, the Interior Ministry of the Serb Republic issued a
statement Tuesday, terming the arrest as a grave incident which
would cause panic among the Serbs and block the free movement of
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
