<HEADLINE> Police Questions Canadian Snowboarder over Drug-Taking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAGANO, Japan, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese police will
question Canadian snowboarder Ross Rebagliati, who was stripped of the
Winter Olympic gold medal after testing positive for marijuana, on
suspicion of violating Japan's drug control law, local news reports
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under Japan's rigid drug control law, possession of the marijuana
carries up to five years imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Reports said the International Olympic Committee (IOC) will be
asked to cooperate in the investigation.
</P>
<P>
Police suspect Rebagliati may have used the drug after coming to
Japan because the IOC reportedly found traces of a substance in
marijuana that oly responds to tests for a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
IOC, however, is not obliged to report to local police when drugs
that violate domestic laws are found in doping tests, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Rebaliati will not face criminal charges unless he is found in
possession of marijuana, even if he consumed it in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian snowboarder, who won the men's snowboarding men's
giant slalom at the current Winter Olympics last Sunday, told Canadian
Olympic officials he had not used marjuana since April last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
