<HEADLINE> Snow Hampers Rescue Work in Quake-Hit N. Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Inclement weather was
hampering relief operations of the United Nations and other
international aid agencies in the quake-stricken Takhor Province
in Northern Afghanistan, U.N. officials said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There is about 20 centimeter snow there and no relief plane
could get into northern Afghanistan," said a U.N. official here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Some reports said a relief helicopter from Tajikistan could
only land in the snow-clad Takhor, where more than 4,000 were
killed and many injured in last week's powerful earthquake and
strong aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
A Pakistan Air Force C-130 plane Monday carried badly needed
blankets and medicine for the quake-affected people.
</P>
<P>
Rupert Colville, the U.N. spokesman in Islamabad, said
Wednesday that a five-truck convoy laden with some 50 tons of
wheat was stuck up and could not reach the quake-hit region due to
heavy snow.
</P>
<P>
"There are really catastrophic weather conditions there and we
are trying to send at least desperately needed plastic sheets for
the shelterless people," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. official said some five to six relief aircraft would
be flying to Takhor Thursday provided the weather situation
improves there.
</P>
<P>
He said the initial death toll of about 4,000 seemed accurate
as the devastating quake caused widespread damage in the remote
region bordering Tajikistan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
