<BODY>
<HEADLINE> El Nino Contributes to Grain Shortage in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTA FE DE BOGOTA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Colombian grain
growers are forecasting a possible shortage in grain production in
the country due to the meteorological phenomenon of "El Nino,"
National Federation of Traders (Fenalco) said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This situation could force traders to import at least 3 million
tons of grains from countries such as the United States, Canada,
Argentina and South Africa. The products that may be in short
supply for this year include corn, sorghum, wheat and barley.
</P>
<P>
According to figures from Fenalco, El Nino caused a reduction
of production in crop-growing land areas in 1997. Arable land was
reduced to 772,186 hectares, which was 6 percent less than that of
1996 and 35 percent less than in 1990.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, grain production fell last year to 1.53
million tons, a decline of 10 percent from 1996 and 29 percent
from 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
