<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based Newspapers:
</P>
<P>
"People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Central Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC)
hosted an evening party yesterday at the Great Hall of the People
in Beijing to celebrate the traditional Chinese Lantern Festival.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 noted intellectuals attended the gathering along with
a number of senior Chinese leaders, including CPC central
committee General Secretary Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng, Vice
Premier Zhu Rongji, and Li Ruihuan, Liu Huaqing, Hu Jintao and
Wei Jianxing.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin said here yesterday that developing
long-term, good-neighborly ties between China and the Republic of
Korea (ROK) is in the fundamental interests of both peoples.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, in meeting with Kim Jong-pil, honorary president of the
Liberal Democratic Union of the Ruling Coalition of the Republic
of Korea, added that Sino-ROK friendly relations and mutually
beneficial cooperation are conducive to peace, stability and
development in the region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng met with Pakistan Prime Minister Mohammad
Navas Sharif yesterday and reiterated China's opposition to the
use of force to solve the current Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
Li said China is highly concerned about developments relating
to the weapons inspection crisis in Iraq. He also expressed his
deep concern about the escalating situation.
</P>
<P>
-- Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, met with New
Zealand Deputy Prime Minister Winston Peters and a friendship
delegation from the city of Taurange yesterday afternoon in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China's top legislator Qiao Shi spoke highly of the
efficient and successful work of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) government yesterday. He expressed
confidence over Hong Kong's ability to overcome current economic
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
-- China has greatly reduced death sentences since adopting of
the newly revised criminal law in October last year.
</P>
<P>
"The greater restriction on capital punishment shows that China
cherished the lives of criminals," said Zhang Jun, a judge from
the Supreme People's Court, yesterday in Beijing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
