<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serbs Removed "Sarajevo Wall" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Bosnian Serbs on Wednesday
afternoon removed a wall they began erecting between the Federal
Croat-Muslim and Serb part of Sarajevo on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Reports of Croatian News Agency from Sarajevo said the wall was
removed after representatives of international organizations in
Bosnia-Herzegovina said freedom of movement must be ensured
throughout the country, including along the inter-entity
separation line in Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
About 200 Bosnian Serbs started building the wall in the
district of Dobrinja in protest against the arrest of Goran Vasic,
suspected of killing Bosnian vice-Premier Hakija Turajlic in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The circumstances surrounding Vasic's arrest are being
investigated by the International Police Task Force, due to
suspicions that he had not been arrested by Sarajevo police but by
members of an unauthorized secret Bosniak (Muslim) service.
</P>
<P>
Dragan Savic, who organized the building
of the wall, said the wall was removed in "understanding towards the
international community which is trying to solve the issue of
Vasic's arrest."
</P>
<P>
Savic threated that they would build "a real wall" and
protest throughout the Bosnian Serb entity if Sarajevo police
failed to surrender Vasic to the Bosnian Serb entity.
</P>
<P>
The Bosnian Serbs who gathered in Dobrinja were visited by the
head of the UN mission in Bosnia, Elizabbeth Rehn.
</P>
<P>
The report said, according to the spokeswoman of the
international High Representatives office, Aisling Burne, the
High Representative is disappointed that Bosnian Serbs act
this way when progress has been made in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
UN spokesman in Sarajevo Aleksandar Ivanko said the Bosnian
Serb police were requested to ensure the removal of the wall and
undisturbed crossing of the inter-entity separation line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
