<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Coal Mines Develop Farming On Wasteland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, February 12 (Xinhua) -- The city of Huaibei, a coal
producer in east China's Anhui Province, has found a good way to
bring some of its vast rundown areas back to life, by developing
farming.
</P>
<P>
A large amount of land that used to produce 19 million tons of
coal annually was abandoned when it was mined out and sank and
became marshland or a refuse dump.
</P>
<P>
There are some 11,666 ha. of this wasteland in Huaibei on more
than 10 percent of the city's cultivable land, leaving 220,000
local farmers without land to till.
</P>
<P>
To solve this problem, the local government has come up with
different means of developing environment-friendly farming by
raising fresh-water fish, poultry, livestock, and fruits and
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
The Huaibei Power Plant is also using coal-ash as landfill and
has planted 213 ha. of trees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0321 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Has Too Many Theme Parks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- Some Chinese are saying that
the country has too many theme parks and should think twice before
starting construction work on any new ones.
</P>
<P>
The construction boom started in the 1980s, when the theme park
was introduced to China, according to "China Economic Times".
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, the large city of Shanghai was worrying
about the absence of theme parks, but now, almost each suburban
county boasts several such attractions.
</P>
<P>
There are also several in surrounding cities like Wuxi and
Suzhou. Along the 150-kilometer railway line from Shanghai to
Wuxi, there are some 20 theme parks.
</P>
<P>
Song Dynasty City in scenic Hangzhou turned out to be a good
business with about three million visitors annually, but the eight
more theme parks planned for the city are thought by some experts
to be too much.
</P>
<P>
Because of the excessive number, business at some of Shanghai's
theme parks is sluggish and some have even gone bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
The high price of tickets, which ranges from 40 yuan (about 5
US dollars) to 100 yuan (about 13 US dollars), also scares some
visitors away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Non-State Sector Gains Share in National Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 12 (Xinhua) -- China's non-state-owned sector
has increased its ratio in the national economy as the country
steps up its economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
Individually-run and private enterprises turned to the state
coffer 44.1 billion yuan in taxes between January and October last
year, up 23 percent from the same 1996 period, according to the
State Administration of Taxation (SAT).
</P>
<P>
Taxes collected from overseas-funded enterprises soared 32
percent to 77.8 billion yuan during that period, while those from
collectively-run enterprises rose three percent to 100.1 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
The figures indicate that the non-state sector has become a
major driving force behind the growth of China's fiscal revenues,
the SAT said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the State Administration for Industry
and Commerce show that at the end of last year, China had more
than 28 million individually-run industrial and commercial
businesses employing a total of 55 million people.
</P>
<P>
The country also had over 800,000 private enterprises with a
total work force of more than six million.
</P>
<P>
Employees of the individually-run and private businesses
include workers, farmers, intellectuals, resigned officials and
retirees.
</P>
<P>
As China quickens the pace of the restructuring of its state
enterprises, millions of workers are displaced each year, while the
overall work force increases at an annual rate of nearly 10
million people.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, the non-state-owned sector has become
a major source for employing the displaced workers and new
job seekers. Last year alone individually-run businesses and
private enterprises employed more than 900,000 displaced workers
nationwide, with another 1.9 million laid-off workers applying to
run businesses or enterprises of their own. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0323 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian President Stresses Need for Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu said Wednesday that stability is the top
priority of the country.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to all political parties and forces to support the
new government to "build" rather than "destroy" the country.
</P>
<P>
Constantinescu made the remarks at the inauguration of five new
ministers which marked the end of a two-week political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The crisis was triggered on January 29 when the Democratic
Party decided to withdraw from the seven-party coalition
government led by Prime Minister Victor Ciorbea because of its
differences with the largest ruling party, the National Peasants'
Party.
</P>
<P>
The two sides later agreed to continue their cooperation and
Prime Minister Ciorbea nominated five new ministers to take over
the vacancies in his government following the withdrawal of the
Democratic Party which now supports the government conditionally.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to members of the reshuffled cabinet, Constantinescu
said that politicians and businessmen around the world are
following closely the situation. Romania has witnessed two major
government reshuffles since December last year.
</P>
<P>
"Disturbance is beneficial to nobody," the president said. The
country needs a clear political prospect so that the government
could take resolute measures to deal with problems facing the
country according to the wishes of the people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
