<HEADLINE> Clinton to Visit Five African Nations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
will make his first visit as president to five African nations
from March 22 to April 2, the White House announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said the trip will cover
Ghana, Uganda, South Africa, Botswana and Senegal and the main aim
is to highlight the U.S. partnership with Africa and promote
economic relations between the United States and the African
nations.
</P>
<P>
"During the trip, the president will highlight the new U.S.
partnership with Africa -- a vibrant continent increasingly open
to democracy and free markets -- and efforts to promote human
rights and prevent future conflicts," McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's tour will be the first by a U.S. president to
sub-Saharan Africa since Jimmy Carter went to Nigeria and Liberia
in 1978. George Bush made a brief visit to Somalia in late 1992
and early 1993 to visit U.S. forces there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
