<HEADLINE> Li Meets With Belgian Senate, Chamber Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Vice Premier
Li Lanqing Wednesday held talks with both heads of Senate and
Chamber of Deputies of Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived in Brussels on Sunday with a delegation of
around 50 people, Wednesday met with President of the Belgian
Senate Frank Swaelen and President of the Chamber of Deputies,
Raymond Langendries.
</P>
<P>
Li said China attached much importance to its relations with
Belgium and expressed his satisfaction with the smooth development
of the relationship in recent years.
</P>
<P>
He told them that he had held constructive talks and meetings
with Belgian authorities during his visit to the country so far.
He believed that the visit would play a positive role in the
further development of their bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Li said that relations between parliaments was an important
part of any bilateral relationship, adding that the National
People's Congress and the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference had very good relations with Belgium's Senate and
Chamber of Deputies.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed the planned joint visit by Swaelen and Langendries
within this year, which he said would enhance the mutual
understanding between parliaments of the two countries and promote
the development of the friendly cooperation between them.
</P>
<P>
Langendries said a good relationship between parliaments of
both sides would play an important role in strengthening both the
Sino-Belgian ties and the relations between China and the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
Swaelen told Li that enterpreneurs from both countries were
having a very good cooperation, which he believed would play a
constructive role in enhancing their bilateral relationship.
</P>
<P>
Li also attended a banquet held by the Belgian-Chinese Economic
and Commercial Council and the Belgian Foreign Trade Board
Wednesday. He delivered a speech on China's current economic
situation and the financial crisis in east Asia at the banquet,
which more than 200 people attended. 
</P>
</TEXT>
