<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> (Updated) Clinton Asks Senate to Approve NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday asked the Senate to approve the accords that will bring
Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic into the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
A ceremony, at which Clinton transmitted to the Senate the
protocols of ratification on admitting the new members, was held
at the State Department, opening the president's campaign to
enlarge the 16-nation alliance.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Clinton reiterated that the expansion
will make the alliance stronger, Europe more stable and undivided.
</P>
<P>
"These three states will add some 200,000 troops to the
alliance," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"A larger NATO will be a better deterrent against aggressors of
the future. It will deepen the ranks of those who stand with us
should deterrents fail," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
The ceremony was attended by Vice President Al Gore, Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, Senator Joseph R. Biden, Senator
William Roth and the foreign ministers of Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Albright said, "Ultimately, we are
building a larger NATO because America has a vital interest in the
security of Europe, one that has always extended to the central
and eastern parts of that continent."
</P>
<P>
"We are doing this because NATO is the key to protecting that
interest. It's our sword and our shield, the greatest war
deterrent in history, the most powerful, credible, effective
instrument we have for joint action with nations that share our
values," she added.
</P>
<P>
Biden echoed with the same views. "NATO is the cornerstone of
American leadership and the foundation for security throughout the
transatlantic community."
</P>
<P>
"I firmly believe that NATO provides the best architecture on
which we can build a united Europe, a Europe that is a vibrant and
active partner of the United States," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Above all, the accession of the Czech Republic, Hungary and
Poland will be a historic step in the construction of an inclusive
security system where peace and stability are the defining
features of post-Cold War years," affirmed the senator.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the 16-member alliance decided to accept Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic as new members by 1999. But the
decision needs to be ratified by legislation of the members.
</P>
<P>
The plan has been so far ratified by Canada and Denmark. The
U.S. Senate is scheduled to vote in March on the move, which is
strongly opposed by Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
