<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Civic, Religious Leaders Oppose Attack on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. religious groups and
civic organizations Wednesday rallied in front of the White House,
demonstrating their will to oppose bombing Iraq by the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Gordaon Clark, the executive director of the Peace Action,
which sponsored the rally, said at the gathering that the U.S.
policy toward Iraq was "politically inept, strategically perilous
and morally bankrupt."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. is blundering headlong into one of the greatest
geopolitical quagmires of this century, with virtually no thought
whatsoever to the myriad of potentially disastrous consequences
which could follow," Clark said, who leads the Peace Action, the
largest grassroots peace organization in the United States.
</P>
<P>
He said bombing could only kill thousands of innocent people,
men, women and children while nothing could be solved as the
Clinton administration expects.
</P>
<P>
He called for sustained diplomacy instead of military action,
saying, "While bombing Iraq may be the easy answer to diverting
public attention from the current domestic news, there is no quick
or `easy' solution to the problems in Iraq. Only sustained
diplomacy can address the issues."
</P>
<P>
The United States has already assembled a mighty force
including warplanes and warships in the Gulf for a preparation of
an air strike on Iraq. And more warplanes are expected to depart
Thursday for the region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Marine Corps General Anthony Zinni, the commander of the
U.S. force in the Middle East, said Wednesday that the U.S. force
there would be ready to strike Iraq within about a week or so.
</P>
<P>
At the rally, the American Muslim Council, a religious group,
released a statement, urging President Bill Clinton to take "all
necessary and appropriate action," but not military action, to
deal with the current Iraqi crisis over weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
"Military strike against the nation of Iraq would be an unjust
and unwise course of action and would comprise the third part of a
triple victimization of the Iraqi people," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The American Muslim Council called on "the Muslim world and
American Muslims to play their Islamic role" in stopping a
possible attack on Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wolf Fassett, the general secretary of the General Board of
Church and Society of the United Methodist Church, also called on
President Clinton "to end all preparations for war and to use
diplomatic means and other necessary resources to find a
nonviolent solution" that would halt the suffering and death of
Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
