<HEADLINE> US Warplanes to Depart for Gulf Thursday. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Nineteen U.S. warplanes
will leave their bases in the United States for the Gulf Thursday
and Friday to join a U.S. military force already stationed there,
prepared to stage a fierce air strike on Iraq, defense officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The planes, ordered to the region by Defense Secretary William
Cohen, will arrive at bases in the region by the weekend, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Six F-16 fighter jets will take off from Shaw Air Force Base in
South Carolina early Thursday and are expected to go to Bahrain.
Later Thursday, six B-52 bombers will leave Barksdale Air Force
base in Louisiana and a B-1 bomber will take off from Ellsworth
Air Force base, South Dakota.
</P>
<P>
Early Friday, six radar-evading F-117A stealth fighters will
depart Holloman Air Force base, New Mexico, for the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The B-52 bombers are expected to join eight other B-52s now at
a British air base on the Indian Ocean island of Diego Garcia.
</P>
<P>
The stealth fighters are expected to join six other F-117As now
in Kuwait, and the B-1 bomber is expected to go to Bahrain, where
two U.S. B-1s are already stationed.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-three tankers and other support planes will also be sent
to the region. And the total of the aircraft then will reach more
than 350 in the area.
</P>
<P>
The additional warplanes were requested by Marine Corps General
Anthony Zinni. He said Wednesday that the U.S. force would be
prepared to strike Iraq within a week if necessary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
