<HEADLINE> U.S. Nationwide Home Prices Rise Strongly in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. nationwide typical
home prices grew more than three times faster than that of the
inflation rate, the National Association of Realtors reported here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Southern and Midwestern cities dominated the list of cities
with the biggest increases in home prices in 1997, according to
the association.
</P>
<P>
The largest increases for existing homes, from the fourth
quarter of 1996 to the fourth quarter of 1997, was registered in
Charleston of South Carolina where it's median home price jumped
16.7 percent to 110,500 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
It was followed by Des Moines, up 15.5 percent; San Francisco,
14.1 percent; Fort Myers, sla., 13.5 percent, and Lexington, Ky.,
11.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, the median price rose 6.2 percent to 124,800
dollars. It was nearly double the 3.3 percent rise a year earlier,
the biggest fourth quarter-to-fourth quarter gain in six years.
The growth clearly surpassed overall inflation, which was just 1.7
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
By region, prices last year rose 7.4 percent in the West, 7
percent in the Midwest, 6.9 percent in the South and 4.6 percent
in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
Only 10 cities of the 134 on the Realtors' list showed fourth
quarter-to-fourth quarter price drops which include Honolulu, down
10 percent to a median of 300,000 dollars, led the list, followed
by Richland, Washington, down 7.1 percent, and Trenton, New
Jersey, down 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Nationally, price gains were supported by a record 4.73 million
sales of existing single-family homes and co-ops in 1997. Those in
turn were boosted by low mortgage rates and strong employment
incomes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
