<DOCNO> XIE19980212.0348 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Changes Lending Rates on Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American
Development Bank Wednesday announced changes in lending rates on
the convertible-currency portion of loans from ordinary capital
for the first semester of 1998.
</P>
<P>
For outstanding balances of currency-pool adjustable rate loans
approved after January 1, 1990, the lending rate is 6.62 percent
per year in first half of 1998 as compared with 6.59 percent per
year in the second semester of 1997.
</P>
<P>
The lending rate applicable to outstanding balance of
adjustable rate loans in U.S. dollars from the single currency
facility (SCF) is 6.99 percent. For loans denominated in German
marks the rate is 6.36 percent while for Japanese yen, 3 percent
and for Swiss francs, 4.31 percent.
</P>
<P>
The previous SCF lending rates in effect, during the second
semester 1997, were U.S. dollars 6.97 percent, German marks 6.66
percent, Japanese yen 3.37 percent and Swiss francs 4.58 percent.
</P>
<P>
The full credit fee, which in most cases is 0.75 percent, will
be charged during second semester 1997. The full inspection fee of
1 percent will be charged during first semester 1998 as against
0.85 percent during the second semester 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
