<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey on Iraq Crisis: Not to Take Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Referring to Turkey's
speculated role in a possible U.S. attack against Iraq, Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz said Wednesday that no one should expect
Turkey to throw itself in the middle of everything and "take
risks."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a parliamentary group of his Motherland Party
(ANAP), Yilmaz said that the current crisis between the United
States and Iraq over arms inspection would severely affect Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He said "No one should expect Turkey to take risks without
negotiating with all related foreign parties, and moreover,
especially when there is nothing being demanded from us."
</P>
<P>
There has been a wide speculation if Turkey, a U.S. ally in the
region, would allow U.S. warplanes to take off from its territory
to launch possible air strikes against Iraq. Ankara did so to the
allied forces during the 1991 Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
Yilmaz said if the U.S. forces ask for military support from
Turkey this time, the decision would only be made by the Turkish
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The policy of our government is solely formulated with
Turkey's interests in mind. We have done all we can in looking for
a peaceful solution... Our armed forces are taking every
precaution required against all odds," the Turkish prime minister
added
</P>
<P>
"From now on, we want Iraq to comply with the U.N. resolutions
and the U.N. to take steps toward fully lifting the sanctions
imposed on Iraq," the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a possible U.S. military strike against Iraq,
Turkish Deputy Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit told members of his
Democratic Left Party Wednesday that "It is of course worrying us,
if that is true. This would mean a superpower like the United
States is entering a war without predicting its consequences."
</P>
<P>
Ecevit also called on the U.S. administration to hold more
dialogs with Turkey while formulating its policies on Iraq since
Turkey is concerned about its southern neighbor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
