<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Wants to Join NATO in Second Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 11 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria seeks to join the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) in a second wave of the
alliance's expansion, and is rapidly upgrading its armed forces,
said Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A NATO membership would make relations between Bulgaria and
Russia "more stable and less ambiguous," the visiting leader told
reporters at the National Press Club.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov said Greece and Turkey backed Bulgaria's candidacy to
join NATO and improving relations between these traditional rivals
was one of his diplomatic priorities.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov, who started his visit to the U.S. last Thursday,
discussed NATO membership and other issues with President Bill
Clinton at a meeting Tuesday that included Vice President Al Gore
and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
He also met separately with Attorney General Janet Reno to talk
about his government's efforts to crack down on the manufacture of
pirated compact discs.
</P>
<P>
"My country's strategic choice of membership in the European
Union and NATO is no hostile act vis-a-vis Russia," Stoyanov wrote
in an article published on Tuesday's edition of The Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
"It corresponds fully with our determination to develop our
relations with that vast state on the basis of mutual benefit and
respect of our sovereignty and national dignity," he added.
</P>
<P>
NATO leaders agreed last July that Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic will be accepted as new members by 1999, and the
alliance's door, however, remains open to other Central and
Eastern European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
