<HEADLINE> US Defense Secretary Ends Gulf Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Defense Secretary
William Cohen left for Russia Wednesday evening after ending a
four-day Gulf tour to seek support for a possible U.S.-led
military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During his tour which started on Sunday, Cohen met with
leaders of all the six Gulf Arab states and discussed with them
the current crisis between Iraq and the United Nations over arms
inspection.
</P>
<P>
He also inspected U.S. military bases in the region, including
a U.S. nuclear site in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The six Gulf Arab states are Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, the
United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar and Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
Cohen pointed out during his tour that if Iraq wants to avert
the strike, it must allow U.N. arms inspectors access to suspected
chemical or biological weapons sites and comply with all the U.N.
Security Council's resolutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
