<DATE_TIME> 1998-02-11 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain: No Deadline for Diplomacy on Iraq Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, February 11 (Xinhua) -- British Minister of State
for Foreign Affairs Derek Fatchett said here Wednesday the United
States and Britain do not set a deadline for diplomatic efforts to
defuse a crisis over arms inspections in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett told a press conference that London and Washington
give "perfect time" to the diplomatic efforts to resolve the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
"The British government is working hard for a diplomatic
solution (to the crisis) and that is our priority," he said.
</P>
<P>
The British official, however, said that options will be
"narrowing down" for Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, who he said
is holding the key to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Saddam "has the ability to resolve the crisis quickly," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett warned of fewer options for Saddam if he fails to
comply with the U.N. Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has barred the U.N. arms inspectors charged with
eliminating its weapons of mass destruction from searching suspect
sites, including presidential palaces.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. and Britain, strengthening their military build-up in
the Gulf, say they will attack Iraq to force its compliance with
the arms inspections if the international diplomatic efforts fail.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett said a coalition against Iraq is taking shape and
being strengthened "day by day."
</P>
<P>
Six nations, namely Australia, Canada, Germany, Oman, Kuwait
and Bahrain have decided to back a possible attack by the U.S. and
Britain.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett denied reports that he is seeking the United Arab
Emirates' support for the possible military strike against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"My visit is to underline Britain's commitment to the Gulf and
desire to consult with friends in the region about the current
crisis between the United Nations and Iraq," he said.
</P>
<P>
Fatchett arrived in the region early in the day. He came here
after a visit to Oman. He will travel to Egypt Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
